{"title_page": "Akrotiri and Dhekelia", "text_new": "{{short description|British Overseas Territory}}\n{{coord|34|35|N|32|59|E|type:city|display=title}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox dependency\n| name = Akrotiri and Dhekelia\n| settlement_type = [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]]\n| official_name = Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia\n| anthem = \"[[God Save the Queen]]\"<br /><div style=\"display:inline-block;margin-top:0.4em;\">[[File:United States Navy Band - God Save the Queen.ogg]]</div>\n| image_map = Akrotiri and Dhekelia in United Kingdom.svg\n| map_caption = Location of Akrotiri and Dhekelia (red)\n| mapsize = 250px\n| image_map2 = Cyprus_SBAsInRed.png\n| map_caption2 = Location of Akrotiri and Dhekelia (pink)<br>on [[Geography of Cyprus|Cyprus]] (pink, grey, and beige)\n| mapsize2 = 250px\n| subdivision_type = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name = [[United Kingdom]]\n| established_title2 = [[London-Z\u00fcrich Agreements|Treaty of Establishment]]\n| established_date2 = 16 August 1960\n| official_languages = [[English language|English]]\n| common_languages = {{hlist|[[Greek language|Greek]]|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]}}\n| capital = [[Episkopi Cantonment|Episkopi]]\n| largest_settlement = [[Akrotiri (village)|Akrotiri]]\n| largest_settlement_type = civilian settlement\n| government_type = ''De facto'' [[stratocracy|stratocratic]] [[Dependent territory|dependency]] under a [[constitutional monarchy]]\n| leader_title1 = [[Monarchy of the UK|Monarch]]\n| leader_name1 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| leader_title2 = Administrator\n| leader_name2 = Major-General [[Robert Thomson (British Army officer)| Robert Thomson]] ''[[ex officio]]''\n| leader_title3 = [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK government]] minister\n| leader_name3 = [[Christopher Pincher]]\n| area_km2 = 254\n| area_sq_mi = <!--Do not remove per [[WP:MOSNUM]]-->\n| area_land_km2 =\n| percent_water =\n| population_estimate = 15,700<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/ax.html |title=Akrotiri |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |work=[[The World Factbook]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| population_estimate_year = 2011\n| population_density_km2 = \n| population_density_sq_mi = <!--Do not remove per [[WP:MOSNUM]]-->\n| population_density_rank = \n| pop_den_footnote =\n| currency = [[Euro]] (\u20ac)\n| currency_code = EUR\n| timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset = +02:00\n| timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +03:00\n| drives_on = left\n| calling_code = [[Telephone numbers in Cyprus|+357]]\n| postal_code_type = [[Postcodes in the United Kingdom#British Overseas Territories|UK postcode]]\n| postal_code = BFPO 57 / BF1 2AT (Akrotiri)<br />BFPO 58 / BF1 2AU (Dhekelia)\n| iso_code =\n| cctld =\n}}\nThe '''Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia'''<ref name=\"BNA1981\">{{cite web |url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1981/61 |title=British Nationality Act 1981 - SCHEDULE 6 British Overseas Territories  | publisher= UK Government |date=September 2016}}</ref> ({{abbr|abbr.|abbreviated}} '''SBA'''; {{lang-el|\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c7\u03ad\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03c9\u03bd \u0392\u03ac\u03c3\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u0391\u03ba\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03b7\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03ad\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1\u03c2}}, ''Perioch\u00e9s Kyr\u00edarchon V\u00e1seon Akrotir\u00edou ke Dek\u00e9lias''; {{lang-tr|Egemen \u00dcs B\u00f6lgeleri A\u011frotur ve Dikelya}}) is a [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] on the [[Geography of Cyprus|island of Cyprus]]. The areas, which include British military bases and installations, as well as other land, were retained by the British under the 1960 treaty of independence, signed by the [[United Kingdom]], [[Greece]], [[Turkey]] and representatives from the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities, which granted independence to the [[Crown colony]] of Cyprus. The territory serves an important role as a station for [[signals intelligence]] and provides a vital strategic part of the United Kingdom communications gathering and monitoring network in the Mediterranean and the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigthink.com/strange-maps/the-worlds-five-military-empires|title=The World's Five Military Empires|date=2017-07-10|website=Big Think|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://breakingdefense.com/2019/12/pull-us-troops-out-of-turkey-former-eucom-deputy/|title=Pull US Troops Out of Turkey: Former EUCOM Deputy|last=Wald|first=Charles|date=December 4, 2019|website=Breaking Defense|language=en-US|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Following UK permission, the [[United States]] was given a limited, short-term presence on the British bases between 2013 and 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2018/10/11/anastasiades-stays-mum-on-secret-us-base/|title=Anastasiades stays mum on \u2018secret\u2019 US base (Updated: adds former spy chief)|last=Hazou|first=Elias|date=2018-10-11|website=Cyprus Mail|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{main|History of Cyprus since 1878}}\n[[File:6903 b01 Garrison officers mess Dhekelia.jpg|thumb|Inside the officers' mess, c. March 1969]]\nThe Sovereign Base Areas were created in 1960 by the [[London and Zurich Agreements]], when Cyprus achieved independence from the [[British Empire]]. The United Kingdom desired to retain sovereignty over these areas, as this guaranteed the use of UK military bases on Cyprus, including [[RAF Akrotiri]], and a garrison of the [[British Army]]. The importance of the bases to the British is based on the strategic location of the island, at the eastern edge of the Mediterranean, close to the [[Suez Canal]] and the Middle East; the ability to use the RAF base as staging post for military aircraft; and for training.\n\n[[File:6903 a38 Garrison officers mess Dhekelia.jpg|thumb|left|Garrison officers mess Dhekelia, 1969]]\nIn July and August 1961, there was a series of bomb-attacks against the pipeline carrying fresh water to the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.<ref>\"Cyprus Base Pipe Again Broken.\" Times [London, England] 2 Aug. 1961: 10. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 29 Dec. 2017</ref> The pipeline was breached by explosions twelve times.<ref>OUR CORRESPONDENT. \"Another Attack On Cyprus Pipeline.\" Times [London, England] 8 Aug. 1961: 6. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 29 Dec. 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1974, following a military coup by the [[Cypriot National Guard]] attempting to achieve ''[[enosis]]'' (union with [[Greece]]), [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|Turkey invaded the north of Cyprus]], leading to the establishment of the internationally unrecognised [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]]. This did not affect the status of the bases. [[Greek Cypriots]] fleeing from the Turkish forces were permitted to travel through the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area and were given humanitarian aid, with those from [[Achna]] setting up a new village (Dasaki Achnas or Achna Forest) which is still in the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=538|title=PRIO|work=prio-cyprus-displacement.net|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The Turkish advance halted when it reached the edge of the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area to avoid military conflict with the United Kingdom. In the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area a tented refugee camp was set up at \"Happy Valley\" (part of the [[Episkopi Cantonment]])<ref>See [http://www.unmultimedia.org/s/photo/detail/852/0085284.html UN photos] of the refugee tents, and an account of the camp on the [http://www.rafakrotiri.co.uk/episkopi/index.html RAF Akrotiri website]</ref> to house Turkish Cypriots fleeing from Limassol and the villages surrounding the Area, until in 1975 they were flown out of RAF Akrotiri via Turkey to [[northern Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=252|title=PRIO|work=prio-cyprus-displacement.net|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Some [[Greek Cypriot]] refugees remain housed on land in the parts of [[Trachoni]]<ref>See [http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=418 PRIO Centre report on Trachoni], and figures for housing units on [http://www.trachoni.com/english/history.htm Trachoni Village website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313165544/http://www.trachoni.com/english/history.htm |date=13 March 2013 }}</ref> and [[Kolossi]]<ref>See [http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=405 PRIO Centre report on Kolossi]</ref> villages that fall within the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area.<ref>See [http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/legislation/01_02_09_06_PIs/01_02_09_06_49_PI_2008/20080101_PI-41_u.pdf Motor Vehicles and Road Traffic (Motorway and Speed Limits) Order 2008] for grid refs and street names for Trachoni, Kolossi and Achna Forest refugee settlements</ref>\n\n==Current status==\nThe territory is composed of two Base Areas. One is Akrotiri ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03ba\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9}} {{IPA-el|akro\u02c8tiri|pron}}; {{lang-tr|A\u011frotur}} {{IPA-tr|\u02c8a\u02d0\u027eotu\u027e}}), or the '''Western Sovereign Base Area''' ('''WSBA'''), which includes two main bases at [[RAF Akrotiri]] and [[Episkopi Cantonment|Episkopi]], plus all of [[Akrotiri (village)|Akrotiri Village's district]] (including [[Limassol Salt Lake]]) and parts of eleven other village districts.<ref>See map at [http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/ao_akrotiri_maps.htm Akrotiri Area Office page] on SBA Administration website</ref> The other area is [[Dhekelia Cantonment]] ({{lang|el|\u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03ad\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}} {{IPA-el|\u00f0e\u02c8ce\u028ea}}; {{lang|tr|Dikelya}}), or the '''Eastern Sovereign Base Area''' ('''ESBA'''), which includes a base at [[Ayios Nikolaos Station|Ayios Nikolaos]] plus parts of twelve village districts.<ref>See map at [http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/ao_dhekelia_maps.htm Dhekelia Area Office page] on SBA Administration website</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\nIn January 2010, a newspaper article appeared in the British press claiming that as a result of budgetary constraints arising from the [[Great Recession]], the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|British Ministry of Defence]] drew up controversial plans to withdraw the United Kingdom's 3,000 strong garrison and end the use of Cyprus as a staging point for ground forces.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628103702/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6999920.ece |work=The Times |location=London |title=Officer Training Corps faces the axe |date=24 January 2010|accessdate=23 April 2010|first1=Jonathan |last1=Oliver |first2=Michael |last2=Smith}}</ref> The Labour government under whom the proposal appeared was replaced by the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition]] and their defence review did not mention the issue.\n\nOn 15 December 2012 in a written statement to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], the UK's [[Secretary of State for Defence]], [[Philip Hammond]], revealed the findings of a report on the SBA military bases following the completion of a review of their operations by [[Lord Ashcroft]]:\n{{quote|The Sovereign Base areas are in a region of geo-political importance and high priority for the United Kingdom's long term national security interests ... Our military personnel, United Kingdom civilians and locally employed personnel in the Sovereign Base Areas make a major contribution to the national security of the United Kingdom and will continue to do so in the future.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-vote-office/9-Defence-Cyprus.pdf |work=UK Parliamentary Statement |location=London |title=Cyprus|date=15 December 2012 |accessdate=24 March 2013 }}</ref>}}\n\n== Governance {{anchor|Constitution and governance}} ==\n\n[[File:USMC CH-53 Akrotiri.jpg|thumb|right|A [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion]] at [[RAF Akrotiri]]]]\n\n[[File:Souvereign Base Areas Police station on Cyprus.JPG|thumb|A SBA Police station in Akrotiri]]\n\nThe SBAs were retained in 1960 to keep military bases in areas under British sovereignty, along with the rights retained to use other sites in what became the territory of the Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.cy/mfa/mfa2006.nsf/All/F207EF6146AA7AFEC22571BF0038DDC6/$file/Treaty%20of%20Establishment.pdf|accessdate=16 June 2013|title=Treaty concerning the establishment of the Republic of Cyprus, with annexes and selected exchanges of notes|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023064308/http://www.mfa.gov.cy/mfa/mfa2006.nsf/All/F207EF6146AA7AFEC22571BF0038DDC6/$file/Treaty%20of%20Establishment.pdf|archivedate=23 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> That makes them different from the other remaining [[British Overseas Territories]], except for the [[British Indian Ocean Territory]] which was similarly carved out of a former colony as a site for a military base, although in that case the base was to be used by the United States and the inhabitants ([[Chagossians]]) were all removed.\n\nThe basic philosophy of their administration was declared by the British government in Appendix O to the 1960 treaty with Cyprus, which provided that the British government intended:\n\n*Not to develop the Sovereign Base Areas for other than military purposes.\n*Not to set up and administer \"colonies\".\n*Not to create customs posts or other frontier barriers between the Sovereign Base Areas and the Republic.\n*Not to set up or permit the establishment of civilian commercial or industrial enterprises except insofar as these are connected with military requirements, and not otherwise to impair the economic, commercial or industrial unity and life of the Island.\n*Not to establish commercial or civilian seaports or airports.\n*Not to allow new settlement of people in the Sovereign Base Areas other than for temporary purposes.\n*Not to expropriate private property within the Sovereign Base Areas except for military purposes on payment of fair compensation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/appdx-o.htm \n|title=SBAA website |publisher=sbaadministration.org |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAppendix O also provides that various ancient monuments in the SBAs (in particular the site and remains of [[Kourion]], the Sanctuary of Apollo [[Hylates]] near Kourion, the Stadium of Curium and the Church and remains of the [[Akrotiri (village)#Holy Monastery of St Nicholas of the Cats|Holy Monastery of St Nicholas of the Cats]]) should be administered by the Republic of Cyprus. The Cypriot government issues licences for antiquity excavation in the SBAs subject to British consent, and any movable antiquities found in excavations or otherwise discovered become Cypriot state property.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.mfa.gr/images/docs/kypriako/treaty_of_establishment.pdf Treaty of Establishment], 1960, p.111-112, p.116</ref>\n\nAccording to the British Ministry of Defence:\n{{quote|Because the SBAs are primarily required as military bases and not ordinary dependent territories, the Administration reports to the Ministry of Defence in London. It has no formal connection with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office or the British High Commission in Nicosia, although there are close informal links with both offices on policy matters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/admin_background.htm |title=SBAA website |publisher=sbaadministration.org |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nThe territory is administered by an [[Administrator of the Government|Administrator]] who is also the [[Commander]] of [[British Forces Cyprus]], which {{as of|2017|February|lc=y}} has been [[James Illingworth|Major-General James Illingworth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/defence-minister-visits-british-forces-in-cyprus |title=Defence minister visits British forces in Cyprus|publisher=GOV.UK |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The Administrator is officially appointed by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|British monarch]] on the advice of the Ministry of Defence. The Administrator has all the executive and legislative authority of a governor of an overseas territory. A Chief Officer is appointed, and is responsible to the Administrator for the day-to-day running of the civil government, with subordinate Area Officers responsible for the civil administration of the two areas. No elections are held in the territory, although British citizens are normally entitled to vote in United Kingdom elections (as British Forces or overseas electors).\n\nThe areas have their own legal system, distinct from the United Kingdom and the Republic of Cyprus. This consists of the laws of the [[Colony of Cyprus]] as of August 1960, amended as necessary. The laws of Akrotiri and Dhekelia are closely aligned with, and in some cases identical to, the laws operating within the Republic of Cyprus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/index.php/court|title=Sovereign Base Area - Court|author=The SBA Administration|work=sbaadministration.org|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The Court of the Sovereign Base Areas is concerned with non-military offences committed by any person within Akrotiri and Dhekelia, and law and order is maintained by the [[Sovereign Base Areas Police]], while offences involving British Forces Cyprus and military law are dealt with by the [[Cyprus Joint Police Unit]]. Fire and rescue services are provided by the Defence Fire and Risk Management Organisation through stations at Episkopi, Akrotiri, Dhekelia and Ayios Nikolayos. The Defence Medical Services provide emergency ambulance cover based from medical centres in the main bases. All emergency services are accessible from any telephone using the Europe-wide emergency number 112.\n\n== Geography ==\n\n[[File:CIA-Akrotiri.png|240px|thumb|Map of Akrotiri, Western Sovereign Base Area, [[British Forces Post Office|BFPO]] 57]]\n[[File:CIA-Dhekelia.png|240px|thumb|Map of Dhekelia, Eastern Sovereign Base Area, [[British Forces Post Office|BFPOs]] 58 & 59]]\n{{see also|Geography of Cyprus}}\n\nAkrotiri and Dhekelia cover 3% of the land area of Cyprus, a total of {{convert|254|km\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} (split {{convert|123|km\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} (48.5%) at Akrotiri and {{convert|131|km\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} (51.5%) at Dhekelia). 60% of the land is privately owned as freeholds by Cypriot citizens; the other 40% is controlled by the Ministry of Defence as [[the Crown]] leasehold land.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm131008/text/131008w0001.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Written Answers for 08 Oct 2013  (pt 0001)|work=parliament.uk|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-10-08c.169396.h|title=Cyprus|work=theyworkforyou.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> In January 2014, an agreement between the Cypriot and UK governments was signed, ensuring that residents and property owners in the British Bases will enjoy equal rights for the development of property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2014/01/16/historic-bases-deal-to-boost-development/|title='Historic' bases deal to boost development|work=cyprus-mail.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> In addition to Akrotiri and Dhekelia, the Treaty of Establishment also provided for the continued use by the British Ministry of Defence and the British Armed Forces of certain facilities within the Republic of Cyprus, known as ''Retained Sites''.\n\nAkrotiri is located in the south of the island, near the city of [[Limassol]] (or Lemesos). Dhekelia is in the southeast, near [[Larnaca]]. Both areas include military bases, as well as farmland and some residential land. Akrotiri is surrounded by territory controlled by the Republic of Cyprus, but Dhekelia also borders on the [[United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus|United Nations (UN) buffer zone]] and the area controlled by the Turkish forces.\n\n[[Ayia Napa]] lies to the east of Dhekelia. The villages of [[Xylotympou]] and [[Ormideia]], also in the Republic of Cyprus, are enclaves surrounded by Dhekelia. The [[Dhekelia Power Station]], divided by a British road into two parts, also belongs to the Republic of Cyprus. The northern part is an enclave, like the two villages, whereas the southern part is located by the sea, and therefore not an enclave, though it has no territorial waters of its own.\n\nTerritorial waters of {{convert|3|nmi|km|3}} are claimed, and the right [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea|according to the laws of the UN]] to extend the claim of up to {{convert|12|nmi|km|3}} is reserved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130325/text/130325w0002.htm#130325w0002.htm_wqn0 |title=Cyprus |work=Hansard |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:20061019 Episkopi Bay.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Episkopi Bay is on the west coast of Akrotiri.]]\n\n== Wildlife and ecology ==\n\nCyprus is an important [[Bird migration|migration flyway]] for birds between Africa and Europe and [[Bird migration perils|millions of birds are killed yearly]] as they migrate over the island. To protect resident and migratory birds, [[BirdLife Cyprus]] and the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|RSPB]] survey areas of illegal trapping. More than 150 species of birds, over half of conservation concern, have been trapped in nets, or on [[Birdlime|limesticks]], and it is estimated that organised crime gangs earn over 15 million Euros yearly. The dead birds are sold to provide the main ingredient for [[ambelopoulia]] in the Republic of Cyprus; an illegal delicacy served to restaurant diners. The 2015 survey estimated a maximum {{Convert|19|km|abbr=on}} of mist nets across both the Republic and the British Territories, and more than 5,300 limesticks removed, mainly in the Republic. It is estimated that over 2 million birds were killed in 2015 including over 800,000 on British Territories.<ref>{{cite web|title=RSPB Mass killing continues on British military base in Cyprus|url=http://www.birdguides.com/iris/pictures.asp?f=433834|website=BirdGuides|accessdate=16 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120211328/http://www.birdguides.com/iris/pictures.asp?f=433834|archivedate=20 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hundreds of thousands of birds still being illegally killed on British military base in Cyprus but annual increase halted|url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/news/416276-hundreds-of-thousands-of-birds-still-being-illegally-killed-on-british-military-base-in-cyprus-but-annual-increase-halted-|website=RSPB|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> Employing measures such as covert camera surveillance (including a drone), exclusion zones and impounding vehicles, trapping activity at Dhekelia fell by 77,5%. In 2016 an estimated 800,000 birds were killed at Dhekelia and in the following year trapping activity fell by 77,5% and bird deaths to an estimated 180,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Good news from Cyprus |work=Nature's Home |publisher=RSPB |date=Summer 2018 |page=40}}</ref>\n\nThe beaches in the British Sovereign Base Areas (SBAs) are important nesting sites for the endangered green ''Chelonia mydas'' and loggerhead ''Caretta caretta'' turtles. The SBA Environment Department, assisted by a large volunteer effort, has monitored turtle nesting success on SBA beaches since 1990. Disturbance to nesting turtles is an issue in some areas due to activities such as camping, driving on beaches and illegal fishing. Sea turtles in Cyprus are protected as priority species under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance (implementing the provisions of the Habitats Directive), enacted in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctuary 40th anniversary edition: Around the regions - Cyprus Sovereign Base|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/469631/15-07-275_Sanctuary_Magazine__FINAL_lowres_.pdf|author=Dr Phoebe Carter|work=Sanctuary - The Ministry of Defence Sustainability Magazine, no.44, page 98|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, five [[Special Areas of Conservation]] (SACs) were designated in the Cyprus Sovereign Base Areas. The five SACs designated are Akrotiri, Episkopi, Cape Pyla, Dhekelia and Agios Nikolaos.<ref>{{cite web|title=Five SACs designated in the British SBAs in Cyprus|url=http://birdlifecyprus.org/en/news-987-Five_SACs_designated_in_the_British_SBAs_in_Cyprus.html|website=BirdLife Cyprus|accessdate=28 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802100411/http://birdlifecyprus.org/en/news-987-Five_SACs_designated_in_the_British_SBAs_in_Cyprus.html|archivedate=2 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The designations were made under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance and will support the existing network ([[Natura 2000|NATURA 2000]]) of SACs in Cyprus and across Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions on the designation of Special Areas of Conservation within the Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia|url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/images/AEEIC/sac/20151217-ECO_SACs_FAQs_AECO.pdf|website=SBA Administration|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{see also|Languages of Cyprus}}\n\nWhen the areas were being established, the boundaries were deliberately drawn to avoid centres of population. Approximately 15,700 people live in the areas. About 7,700 native Cypriots work in the areas themselves, or on farmland within the boundaries of the areas. The British military and their families make up the rest of the population.<ref>[http://www.indexmundi.com/akrotiri/population.html Akrotiri Population] and [http://www.indexmundi.com/dhekelia/population.html Dhekelia Population]. Retrieved 24 December 2013.</ref>\n\nPersons related to the territory may in theory be eligible to claim the [[British Overseas Territories citizen]]ship (BOTC status) through a personal connection to the areas (i.e., birth on the territory before 1983, or born after 1983 to a parent who were born on the territory before 1983); but unlike most other British Overseas Territories, there is no provision in the [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002|2002 amendment]] of the [[British Nationality Act 1981]] by which British citizenship (with the [[Right of abode (United Kingdom)|right of abode in the United Kingdom]]) can either be claimed through automatic entitlement or be applied for by means of registration, from or through a sole personal connection to the Base Areas. (In comparison, the 2002 act bestowed British citizenship on all other BOTCs.) Hence non-British and non-military personnel with the connection to the territory can only live and work in the UK through their EU (Cypriot) citizenship and not through their BOTC status.\n\nUnder the terms of the 1960 agreement with Cyprus establishing the Sovereign Base Areas, the United Kingdom is committed not to use the areas for civilian purposes. This was stated in 2002 as the primary reason for the exclusion of the areas from the scope of the [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} {{As of |2010}}, around 3,000 troops of [[British Forces Cyprus]] are based at Akrotiri and Dhekelia.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Akrotiri 01-2017 img11 Akrotiri village.jpg|thumb|Akrotiri village]]\n\nNo economic statistics are gathered for Akrotiri and Dhekelia. The main economic activities are the provision of services to the military, as well as limited agriculture. When the territory under the effective control of the Republic of Cyprus switched currencies from the [[Cypriot pound]] to the [[euro]] on 1 January 2008, Akrotiri and Dhekelia followed suit making the Sovereign Base Areas the only territory under British sovereignty to officially use the euro.<ref>Theodoulou, Michael. (27 December 2007). https://web.archive.org/web/20110510204604/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article3097521.ece Euro reaches field that is for ever England], ''The Times''. Retrieved 4 January 2008.</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n[[File:Akrotiri 01-2017 img01 BBC transmitter masts.jpg|thumb|[[BBC World Service]] transmitter masts in Akrotiri]]\n\n[[British Forces Broadcasting Service#BFBS Radio|BFBS Radio 1 and 2]] are broadcast on [[FM broadcasting|FM]] and can be widely received across Cyprus. [[British Forces Broadcasting Service#BFBS Television|BFBS Television]] is now only available to entitled viewers via satellite, having been confined to the SBAs or encrypted in 1997 for copyright reasons,<ref>[http://www.hri.org/news/cyprus/cmnews/1998/98-05-10.cmnews.html#02 BFBS pulls the plug on Larnaca viewers], ''[[Cyprus Mail]]'' 10 May 1998</ref> before BFBS switched off its analogue transmitters in 2009.<ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Screens+go+blank+as+BFBS+TV+switches+off+transmitters.-a0191740458 Screens go blank as BFBS TV switches off transmitters.], ''[[Cyprus Mail]]'', 8 January 2009</ref> The [[British East Mediterranean Relay Station]] is situated locally.\n\n== Transport and communications ==\n[[File:Britse telefooncel op Cyprus.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.6|A British [[red telephone box]] in Dhekelia]]\nCypriot motorways pass through both areas. There is no public airport within the areas, but the [[RAF Akrotiri]] airbase is located there, which has a runway suitable for long-distance flights, but not used for public flights.\n\nThe Base Areas form part of the Republic of Cyprus [[telephone numbering plan]], using the international prefix [[+357]]. Landline numbers are in the same eight-digit format, with the last four digits being the line number. Numbers in Dhekelia begin with the digits '''2474''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/british-forces-overseas-posting-dhekelia-cyprus|title=British forces overseas posting: Dhekelia, Cyprus|work=www.gov.uk|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> while those in Akrotiri begin with the digits '''2527'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/british-forces-overseas-posting-raf-akrotiri-cyprus|title=British Forces overseas posting: RAF Akrotiri, Cyprus|work=www.gov.uk|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> \n\nPostal services are provided by the [[British Forces Post Office]], with mail to Akrotiri being addressed to '''BFPO 57'''<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/482888/bfpo-indicator_list_7dec2015.pdf|title = BFPO Indicator List BFPO Static Postcodes|date = |accessdate = 3 January 2016|website = |publisher = UK Government|last = |first = }}</ref> and mail to Dhekelia and Ayios Nikolaos being addressed to '''BFPO 58'''.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/278799/bfpo_indicator_list_11feb14.pdf BFPO INDICATOR LIST STATIC BRITISH FORCES POST OFFICES]</ref> [[Cyprus Postal Services]] provides postal service for civilian homes and businesses within the Base Areas, then using [[Postal codes in Cyprus|Cypriot postal codes]] and \"Cyprus\" as country on letters from abroad.\n\nThe bases are issued different [[amateur radio]] [[Amateur radio callsigns of the Middle East#Cyprus|call signs]] from the Republic of Cyprus. Amateur radio stations on the bases use the [[International Telecommunication Union]] prefix of \"ZC4\", which is assigned to Great Britain.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SjdQAAAAYAAJ&q=ZC4+radio+call+sign+cyprus&dq=ZC4+radio+call+sign+cyprus Amateur Radio, Volume 59, Issues 1-6] \"Steve Bowden, ZC4BX, recently returned to the UK after three years on Cyprus, where he initiated and managed the ZC4 award.\"</ref> There are about 52 amateurs licensed in this manner. Amateur [[Radio Direction Finding|radio direction finding]] identified RAF Akrotiri as the location of the powerful but now defunct [[Shortwave radio|shortwave]] [[numbers station]] \"[[Lincolnshire Poacher (numbers station)|Lincolnshire Poacher]]\". Several [[HRS antenna|curtain antennas]] there have been identified as being used for these transmissions.<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web | title =  Lincolnshire Poacher | publisher = Numbers and Oddities | url = http://www.numbersoddities.nl | accessdate = 2008-05-25 }}{{Self-published source|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n[[Service Children's Education]] oversees education for children of personnel and [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MoD]] employees. The Eastern Sovereign Base Area is served by Dhekelia Primary School and Ayios Nikolaos Primary School, which are feeders for [[King Richard School, Cyprus|King Richard School]]. The Western Sovereign Base Area is served by Episkopi Primary School and Akrotiri Primary School, which are feeders for [[St. John's School, Cyprus|St. John's School]].\n\n== Travel documents ==\n{{main|Borders of Akrotiri and Dhekelia}}\n\nThere is normally no passport check at the border from Akrotiri or Dhekelia to Cyprus.<ref>[https://www.quora.com/Is-it-possible-to-visit-Akrotiri-or-Dhekelia-the-British-Sovereign-Base-Areas-in-Cyprus-as-a-tourist Is it possible to visit Akrotiri or Dhekelia, the British Sovereign Base Areas in Cyprus, as a tourist?]</ref>{{better source needed|date=November 2019}} Possession of a passport, or an [[National identity cards in the European Economic Area|EU-compliant national identity card]] is generally needed in Cyprus. A passport is required to travel between [[Cyprus]]/SBAs and [[Northern Cyprus]]. Issues concerning the validity of car insurance and customs are specified by SBAs' administration.<ref>[http://www.sbaadministration.org/docs/admin/announcements/Travelling_North.pdf SBA Customs and Immigration] Travelling to Northern Cyprus</ref>\n\n==Brexit implications==\nUnder Article 2(1) of the Protocol, the SBAs are partially part of the EU customs union in three domains: VAT, agriculture and fisheries. However, the SBAs are already outside the EU. Therefore, concerns have been raised about the future status of about 15,000 Cypriots (EU citizens) working in the SBA. Cyprus, [[Ireland]] and [[Spain]] are the only three EU states that conduct bilateral talks with the UK on the Brexit issue. The talks between the UK and the Republic of Cyprus started in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eyes-on-europe.eu/brexits-impacts-cyprus/ |title=Brexit\u2019s obscure impacts: the borders of Cyprus |publisher=Eyes on Europe |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/brexit-a-view-from-cyprus/a-40898512 |title=Brexit: A view from Cyprus |publisher= Deutsche Welle|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\nThe [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] has a protocol on the SBAs, with provisions essentially keeping the state of them.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:12019W/TXT(02)|title= INFORMATION FROM EUROPEAN UNION INSTITUTIONS, BODIES, OFFICES AND AGENCIES|website=eur-lex.europa.eu |format=PDF|access-date=2020-02-03}} page 136</ref><ref>[https://cyprus-mail.com/2020/01/31/foreign-education-ministries-reassure-cypriots-over-brexit/ Foreign, education ministries reassure Cypriots over Brexit - Cyprus Mail]</ref>\n\n== Criticism and disputes ==\nIn July 2001, protests were held at the bases by local Cypriots, unhappy with British plans to construct [[Radio masts and towers|radio masts]] at the bases as part of an upgrade of British military communication posts around the world. Locals claimed the masts would endanger local lives and cause cancer, as well as have a negative impact on wildlife in the area. The British and Cypriot governments jointly commissioned health research from the [[University of Bristol]] and the Ministry of Health of the Republic of Cyprus, and that research project reported in 2005 that there was no evidence of health problems being caused by electromagnetic fields from the antennas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electric-fields.bris.ac.uk/akrotirireport.pdf |title=Bristol University website |publisher=electric-fields.bris.ac.uk |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref> The Sovereign Base Areas Administration has carried out assessments and surveys into the effects on wildlife, which have fed into an \"Akrotiri Peninsula Environmental Management Plan\", published in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/docs/eco/20121002_AKI_PEN_MGT_PLAN.pdf |title=SBAA website |publisher=sbaadministration.org |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the UK offered to cede {{convert|117|km2|sqmi}} of farmland as part of the rejected [[Annan Plan for Cyprus]]. \n\nOn 29 August 2013, during the [[Syrian civil war]], some Cypriot and British media sources speculated that long-range ballistic missiles, fired from Syria in retaliation for proposed British involvement in military intervention against the Syrian government of [[Bashar al-Assad]], could hit Cyprus, and could potentially deliver chemical weapons. In some Cypriot media it was stated that the proposed interdiction of the Syrian civil war, utilising Akrotiri and Dhekelia, could recklessly endanger the Cypriot populations near to those bases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2013/08/29/cyprus-placed-in-the-cross-hairs-of-syria-mess/|title=Cyprus placed in the cross hairs of Syria mess|work=cyprus-mail.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Two days earlier, on 27 August 2013, Cypriot foreign minister [[Ioannis Kasoulides]] had moved to calm Cypriot concerns, saying that the British bases were unlikely to play a major part in any intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2013/08/28/cyprus-will-not-play-major-role-in-any-syria-strikes/|title='Cyprus will not play major role in any Syria strikes'|work=cyprus-mail.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Ayios Nikolaos Station]], in the ESBA, is an [[Signals intelligence#ELINT|ELINT]] (electronic intelligence) listening station of the [[UKUSA Agreement]] intelligence network.<ref>Jeffrey Richelson & Desmond Ball, The Ties the Bind: Intelligence Cooperation between the UKUSA Countries, Unwin Hyman, Boston/London and others, 1990, p.194 note 145.</ref> The UKUSA signals intelligence system is sometimes known as \"[[ECHELON]]\".<ref name=EP>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//NONSGML+REPORT+A5-2001-0264+0+DOC+PDF+V0//EN&language=EN |title=On the existence of a global system for the interception of private and commercial communications (ECHELON interception system), (2001/2098(INI)) |last=Schmid |first=Gerhard |date=11 July 2001 |format=pdf \u2013 194 pages |publisher=European Parliament: Temporary Committee on the ECHELON Interception System |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cyprus|United Kingdom|Geography|Europe}}\n* [[Index of Akrotiri and Dhekelia-related articles]]\n* [[List of British Army installations]]\n* [[List of British overseas territories]]\n* [[Murder of Louise Jensen]]\n* [[Sovereign Base Areas Customs]]\n* [[United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus]]\n* [[Overseas military bases of the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*{{cite book|last=Fouskas |first=Vassilis K. |year=2003 |title=Zones of Conflict: U.S. Foreign Policy in the Balkans and the Greater Middle East |location= |publisher=Pluto Press |pages=93, 111 |isbn=0-7453-2030-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Akrotiri and Dhekelia}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{wikiatlas}}\n* [https://www.sbaadministration.org/index.php Sovereign Base Areas Administration web-pages]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/2794421.stm BBC News \u2013 \"UK offers to cede Cyprus land\"]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/1421365.stm BBC News \u2013 \"Cyprus protesters clash at UK base\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100101150457/http://cyprus-mail.com/features/remembering-our-baby-girl Cyprus Mail, Nathan Morley \u2013 \"Mystery of Dhekelia Cemetery\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100722235519/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/features/dhekelia-60-finest-barracks-world/20100718 Cyprus Mail, Nathan Morley \u2013 \"Dhekelia at 60\"]\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|ax|Akrotiri}}\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|dx|Dhekelia}}\n* [http://www.qaranc.co.uk/theprincessmaryshospital.php The Princess Mary's Hospital RAF Akrotiri]\n* [http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1960/jul/04/cyprus-agreement Cyprus Independence Agreement \u2013 Hansard Official UK Parliament Record]\n* James Rogers and Luis Sim\u00f3n. [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meetdocs/2004_2009/documents/dv/sede300309studype407004_/SEDE300309StudyPE407004_en.pdf The Status and Location of the Military Installations of the Member States of the European Union and Their Potential Role for the European Security and Defence Policy (ESDP).] Brussels: European Parliament, 2009. 25&nbsp;pp.\n\n{{Cyprus topics}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{British dependencies}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n{{Countries of Europe}}\n{{History of Europe}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akrotiri And Dhekelia}}\n[[Category:Akrotiri and Dhekelia| ]]\n[[Category:Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Cyprus and the Commonwealth of Nations]]\n[[Category:English-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British Army deployments]]\n[[Category:British military in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:British Overseas Territories|.Akrotiri and Dhekelia]]\n[[Category:Dependent territories in Europe]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force deployments]]\n[[Category:Southern European countries]]\n[[Category:Sovereign Base Areas]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Western Asian countries]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Overseas Territory}}\n{{coord|34|35|N|32|59|E|type:city|display=title}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox dependency\n| name = Akrotiri and Dhekelia\n| settlement_type = [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]]\n| official_name = Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia\n| anthem = \"[[God Save the Queen]]\"<br /><div style=\"display:inline-block;margin-top:0.4em;\">[[File:United States Navy Band - God Save the Queen.ogg]]</div>\n| image_map = Akrotiri and Dhekelia in United Kingdom.svg\n| map_caption = Location of Akrotiri and Dhekelia (red)\n| mapsize = 250px\n| image_map2 = Cyprus_SBAsInRed.png\n| map_caption2 = Location of Akrotiri and Dhekelia (pink)<br>on [[Geography of Cyprus|Cyprus]] (pink, grey, and beige)\n| mapsize2 = 250px\n| subdivision_type = [[Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name = [[United Kingdom]]\n| established_title2 = [[London-Z\u00fcrich Agreements|Treaty of Establishment]]\n| established_date2 = 16 August 1960\n| official_languages = [[English language|English]]\n| common_languages = {{hlist|[[Greek language|Greek]]|[[Turkish language|Turkish]]}}\n| capital = [[Episkopi Cantonment|Episkopi]]\n| largest_settlement = [[Akrotiri (village)|Akrotiri]]\n| largest_settlement_type = civilian settlement\n| government_type = ''De facto'' [[stratocracy|stratocratic]] [[Dependent territory|dependency]] under a [[constitutional monarchy]]\n| leader_title1 = [[Monarchy of the UK|Monarch]]\n| leader_name1 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| leader_title2 = Administrator\n| leader_name2 = Major-General [[Robert Thomson (British Army officer)| Robert Thomson]] ''[[ex officio]]''\n| leader_title3 = [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK government]] minister\n| leader_name3 = [[Christopher Pincher]]\n| area_km2 = 254\n| area_sq_mi = <!--Do not remove per [[WP:MOSNUM]]-->\n| area_land_km2 =\n| percent_water =\n| population_estimate = 15,700<ref name=\"cia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/resources/the-world-factbook/geos/ax.html |title=Akrotiri |publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agency]] |work=[[The World Factbook]] |accessdate=20 September 2019 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n| population_estimate_year = 2011\n| population_density_km2 = \n| population_density_sq_mi = <!--Do not remove per [[WP:MOSNUM]]-->\n| population_density_rank = \n| pop_den_footnote =\n| currency = [[Euro]] (\u20ac)\n| currency_code = EUR\n| timezone = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset = +02:00\n| timezone_DST = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST = +03:00\n| drives_on = left\n| calling_code = [[Telephone numbers in Cyprus|+357]]\n| postal_code_type = [[Postcodes in the United Kingdom#British Overseas Territories|UK postcode]]\n| postal_code = BFPO 57 / BF1 2AT (Akrotiri)<br />BFPO 58 / BF1 2AU (Dhekelia)\n| iso_code =\n| cctld =\n}}\nThe '''Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia'''<ref name=\"BNA1981\">{{cite web |url=https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1981/61 |title=British Nationality Act 1981 - SCHEDULE 6 British Overseas Territories  | publisher= UK Government |date=September 2016}}</ref> ({{abbr|abbr.|abbreviated}} '''SBA'''; {{lang-el|\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03c7\u03ad\u03c2 \u039a\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03c9\u03bd \u0392\u03ac\u03c3\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u0391\u03ba\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03b7\u03c1\u03af\u03bf\u03c5 \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03ad\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1\u03c2}}, ''Perioch\u00e9s Kyr\u00edarchon V\u00e1seon Akrotir\u00edou ke Dek\u00e9lias''; {{lang-tr|Egemen \u00dcs B\u00f6lgeleri A\u011frotur ve Dikelya}}) is a [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] on the [[Geography of Cyprus|island of Cyprus]]. The areas, which include British military bases and installations, as well as other land, were retained by the British under the 1960 treaty of independence, signed by the [[United Kingdom]], [[Greece]], [[Turkey]] and representatives from the Greek and Turkish Cypriot communities, which granted independence to the [[Crown colony]] of Cyprus. The territory serves an important role as a station for [[signals intelligence]] and provides a vital strategic part of the United Kingdom communications gathering and monitoring network in the Mediterranean and the Middle East.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigthink.com/strange-maps/the-worlds-five-military-empires|title=The World's Five Military Empires|date=2017-07-10|website=Big Think|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://breakingdefense.com/2019/12/pull-us-troops-out-of-turkey-former-eucom-deputy/|title=Pull US Troops Out of Turkey: Former EUCOM Deputy|last=Wald|first=Charles|date=December 4, 2019|website=Breaking Defense|language=en-US|access-date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> Following UK permission, the [[United States]] was given a limited, short-term presence on the British bases between 2013 and 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cyprus-mail.com/2018/10/11/anastasiades-stays-mum-on-secret-us-base/|title=Anastasiades stays mum on \u2018secret\u2019 US base (Updated: adds former spy chief)|last=Hazou|first=Elias|date=2018-10-11|website=Cyprus Mail|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{main|History of Cyprus since 1878}}\n[[File:6903 b01 Garrison officers mess Dhekelia.jpg|thumb|Inside the officers' mess, c. March 1969]]\nThe Sovereign Base Areas were created in 1960 by the [[London and Zurich Agreements]], when Cyprus achieved independence from the [[British Empire]]. The United Kingdom desired to retain sovereignty over these areas, as this guaranteed the use of UK military bases on Cyprus, including [[RAF Akrotiri]], and a garrison of the [[British Army]]. The importance of the bases to the British is based on the strategic location of the island, at the eastern edge of the Mediterranean, close to the [[Suez Canal]] and the Middle East; the ability to use the RAF base as staging post for military aircraft; and for training.\n\n[[File:6903 a38 Garrison officers mess Dhekelia.jpg|thumb|left|Garrison officers mess Dhekelia, 1969]]\nIn July and August 1961, there was a series of bomb-attacks against the pipeline carrying fresh water to the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.<ref>\"Cyprus Base Pipe Again Broken.\" Times [London, England] 2 Aug. 1961: 10. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 29 Dec. 2017</ref> The pipeline was breached by explosions twelve times.<ref>OUR CORRESPONDENT. \"Another Attack On Cyprus Pipeline.\" Times [London, England] 8 Aug. 1961: 6. The Times Digital Archive. Web. 29 Dec. 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1974, following a military coup by the [[Cypriot National Guard]] attempting to achieve ''[[enosis]]'' (union with [[Greece]]), [[Turkish invasion of Cyprus|Turkey invaded the north of Cyprus]], leading to the establishment of the internationally unrecognised [[Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus]]. This did not affect the status of the bases. [[Greek Cypriots]] fleeing from the Turkish forces were permitted to travel through the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area and were given humanitarian aid, with those from [[Achna]] setting up a new village (Dasaki Achnas or Achna Forest) which is still in the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=538|title=PRIO|work=prio-cyprus-displacement.net|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The Turkish advance halted when it reached the edge of the Dhekelia Sovereign Base Area to avoid military conflict with the United Kingdom. In the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area a tented refugee camp was set up at \"Happy Valley\" (part of the [[Episkopi Cantonment]])<ref>See [http://www.unmultimedia.org/s/photo/detail/852/0085284.html UN photos] of the refugee tents, and an account of the camp on the [http://www.rafakrotiri.co.uk/episkopi/index.html RAF Akrotiri website]</ref> to house Turkish Cypriots fleeing from Limassol and the villages surrounding the Area, until in 1975 they were flown out of RAF Akrotiri via Turkey to [[northern Cyprus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=252|title=PRIO|work=prio-cyprus-displacement.net|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Some [[Greek Cypriot]] refugees remain housed on land in the parts of [[Trachoni]]<ref>See [http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=418 PRIO Centre report on Trachoni], and figures for housing units on [http://www.trachoni.com/english/history.htm Trachoni Village website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130313165544/http://www.trachoni.com/english/history.htm |date=13 March 2013 }}</ref> and [[Kolossi]]<ref>See [http://www.prio-cyprus-displacement.net/default.asp?id=405 PRIO Centre report on Kolossi]</ref> villages that fall within the Akrotiri Sovereign Base Area.<ref>See [http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/legislation/01_02_09_06_PIs/01_02_09_06_49_PI_2008/20080101_PI-41_u.pdf Motor Vehicles and Road Traffic (Motorway and Speed Limits) Order 2008] for grid refs and street names for Trachoni, Kolossi and Achna Forest refugee settlements</ref>\n\n==Current status==\nThe territory is composed of two Base Areas. One is Akrotiri ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03ba\u03c1\u03c9\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9}} {{IPA-el|akro\u02c8tiri|pron}}; {{lang-tr|A\u011frotur}} {{IPA-tr|\u02c8a\u02d0\u027eotu\u027e}}), or the '''Western Sovereign Base Area''' ('''WSBA'''), which includes two main bases at [[RAF Akrotiri]] and [[Episkopi Cantonment|Episkopi]], plus all of [[Akrotiri (village)|Akrotiri Village's district]] (including [[Limassol Salt Lake]]) and parts of eleven other village districts.<ref>See map at [http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/ao_akrotiri_maps.htm Akrotiri Area Office page] on SBA Administration website</ref> The other area is [[Dhekelia Cantonment]] ({{lang|el|\u0394\u03b5\u03ba\u03ad\u03bb\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1}} {{IPA-el|\u00f0e\u02c8ce\u028ea}}; {{lang|tr|Dikelya}}), or the '''Eastern Sovereign Base Area''' ('''ESBA'''), which includes a base at [[Ayios Nikolaos Station|Ayios Nikolaos]] plus parts of twelve village districts.<ref>See map at [http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/ao_dhekelia_maps.htm Dhekelia Area Office page] on SBA Administration website</ref>\n\n== Reviews ==\nIn January 2010, a newspaper article appeared in the British press claiming that as a result of budgetary constraints arising from the [[Great Recession]], the [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|British Ministry of Defence]] drew up controversial plans to withdraw the United Kingdom's 3,000 strong garrison and end the use of Cyprus as a staging point for ground forces.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628103702/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6999920.ece |work=The Times |location=London |title=Officer Training Corps faces the axe |date=24 January 2010|accessdate=23 April 2010|first1=Jonathan |last1=Oliver |first2=Michael |last2=Smith}}</ref> The Labour government under whom the proposal appeared was replaced by the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition]] and their defence review did not mention the issue.\n\nOn 15 December 2012 in a written statement to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]], the UK's [[Secretary of State for Defence]], [[Philip Hammond]], revealed the findings of a report on the SBA military bases following the completion of a review of their operations by [[Lord Ashcroft]]:\n{{quote|The Sovereign Base areas are in a region of geo-political importance and high priority for the United Kingdom's long term national security interests ... Our military personnel, United Kingdom civilians and locally employed personnel in the Sovereign Base Areas make a major contribution to the national security of the United Kingdom and will continue to do so in the future.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-vote-office/9-Defence-Cyprus.pdf |work=UK Parliamentary Statement |location=London |title=Cyprus|date=15 December 2012 |accessdate=24 March 2013 }}</ref>}}\n\n== Governance {{anchor|Constitution and governance}} ==\n\n[[File:USMC CH-53 Akrotiri.jpg|thumb|right|A [[United States Marine Corps]] [[Sikorsky CH-53 Sea Stallion]] at [[RAF Akrotiri]]]]\n\n[[File:Souvereign Base Areas Police station on Cyprus.JPG|thumb|A SBA Police station in Akrotiri]]\n\nThe SBAs were retained in 1960 to keep military bases in areas under British sovereignty, along with the rights retained to use other sites in what became the territory of the Republic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mfa.gov.cy/mfa/mfa2006.nsf/All/F207EF6146AA7AFEC22571BF0038DDC6/$file/Treaty%20of%20Establishment.pdf|accessdate=16 June 2013|title=Treaty concerning the establishment of the Republic of Cyprus, with annexes and selected exchanges of notes|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023064308/http://www.mfa.gov.cy/mfa/mfa2006.nsf/All/F207EF6146AA7AFEC22571BF0038DDC6/$file/Treaty%20of%20Establishment.pdf|archivedate=23 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> That makes them different from the other remaining [[British Overseas Territories]], except for the [[British Indian Ocean Territory]] which was similarly carved out of a former colony as a site for a military base, although in that case the base was to be used by the United States and the inhabitants ([[Chagossians]]) were all removed.\n\nThe basic philosophy of their administration was declared by the British government in Appendix O to the 1960 treaty with Cyprus, which provided that the British government intended:\n\n*Not to develop the Sovereign Base Areas for other than military purposes.\n*Not to set up and administer \"colonies\".\n*Not to create customs posts or other frontier barriers between the Sovereign Base Areas and the Republic.\n*Not to set up or permit the establishment of civilian commercial or industrial enterprises except insofar as these are connected with military requirements, and not otherwise to impair the economic, commercial or industrial unity and life of the Island.\n*Not to establish commercial or civilian seaports or airports.\n*Not to allow new settlement of people in the Sovereign Base Areas other than for temporary purposes.\n*Not to expropriate private property within the Sovereign Base Areas except for military purposes on payment of fair compensation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/appdx-o.htm \n|title=SBAA website |publisher=sbaadministration.org |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAppendix O also provides that various ancient monuments in the SBAs (in particular the site and remains of [[Kourion]], the Sanctuary of Apollo [[Hylates]] near Kourion, the Stadium of Curium and the Church and remains of the [[Akrotiri (village)#Holy Monastery of St Nicholas of the Cats|Holy Monastery of St Nicholas of the Cats]]) should be administered by the Republic of Cyprus. The Cypriot government issues licences for antiquity excavation in the SBAs subject to British consent, and any movable antiquities found in excavations or otherwise discovered become Cypriot state property.<ref name=\":0\">[http://www.mfa.gr/images/docs/kypriako/treaty_of_establishment.pdf Treaty of Establishment], 1960, p.111-112, p.116</ref>\n\nAccording to the British Ministry of Defence:\n{{quote|Because the SBAs are primarily required as military bases and not ordinary dependent territories, the Administration reports to the Ministry of Defence in London. It has no formal connection with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office or the British High Commission in Nicosia, although there are close informal links with both offices on policy matters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/admin_background.htm |title=SBAA website |publisher=sbaadministration.org |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nThe territory is administered by an [[Administrator of the Government|Administrator]] who is also the [[Commander]] of [[British Forces Cyprus]], which {{as of|2017|February|lc=y}} has been [[James Illingworth|Major-General James Illingworth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/defence-minister-visits-british-forces-in-cyprus |title=Defence minister visits British forces in Cyprus|publisher=GOV.UK |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The Administrator is officially appointed by the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|British monarch]] on the advice of the Ministry of Defence. The Administrator has all the executive and legislative authority of a governor of an overseas territory. A Chief Officer is appointed, and is responsible to the Administrator for the day-to-day running of the civil government, with subordinate Area Officers responsible for the civil administration of the two areas. No elections are held in the territory, although British citizens are normally entitled to vote in United Kingdom elections (as British Forces or overseas electors).\n\nThe areas have their own legal system, distinct from the United Kingdom and the Republic of Cyprus. This consists of the laws of the [[Colony of Cyprus]] as of August 1960, amended as necessary. The laws of Akrotiri and Dhekelia are closely aligned with, and in some cases identical to, the laws operating within the Republic of Cyprus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/index.php/court|title=Sovereign Base Area - Court|author=The SBA Administration|work=sbaadministration.org|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> The Court of the Sovereign Base Areas is concerned with non-military offences committed by any person within Akrotiri and Dhekelia, and law and order is maintained by the [[Sovereign Base Areas Police]], while offences involving British Forces Cyprus and military law are dealt with by the [[Cyprus Joint Police Unit]]. Fire and rescue services are provided by the Defence Fire and Risk Management Organisation through stations at Episkopi, Akrotiri, Dhekelia and Ayios Nikolayos. The Defence Medical Services provide emergency ambulance cover based from medical centres in the main bases. All emergency services are accessible from any telephone using the Europe-wide emergency number 112.\n\n== Geography ==\n\n[[File:CIA-Akrotiri.png|240px|thumb|Map of Akrotiri, Western Sovereign Base Area, [[British Forces Post Office|BFPO]] 57]]\n[[File:CIA-Dhekelia.png|240px|thumb|Map of Dhekelia, Eastern Sovereign Base Area, [[British Forces Post Office|BFPOs]] 58 & 59]]\n{{see also|Geography of Cyprus}}\n\nAkrotiri and Dhekelia cover 3% of the land area of Cyprus, a total of {{convert|254|km\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} (split {{convert|123|km\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} (48.5%) at Akrotiri and {{convert|131|km\u00b2|0|abbr=on}} (51.5%) at Dhekelia). 60% of the land is privately owned as freeholds by Cypriot citizens; the other 40% is controlled by the Ministry of Defence as [[the Crown]] leasehold land.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmhansrd/cm131008/text/131008w0001.htm|title=House of Commons Hansard Written Answers for 08 Oct 2013  (pt 0001)|work=parliament.uk|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2013-10-08c.169396.h|title=Cyprus|work=theyworkforyou.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> In January 2014, an agreement between the Cypriot and UK governments was signed, ensuring that residents and property owners in the British Bases will enjoy equal rights for the development of property.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2014/01/16/historic-bases-deal-to-boost-development/|title='Historic' bases deal to boost development|work=cyprus-mail.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> In addition to Akrotiri and Dhekelia, the Treaty of Establishment also provided for the continued use by the British Ministry of Defence and the British Armed Forces of certain facilities within the Republic of Cyprus, known as ''Retained Sites''.\n\nAkrotiri is located in the south of the island, near the city of [[Limassol]] (or Lemesos). Dhekelia is in the southeast, near [[Larnaca]]. Both areas include military bases, as well as farmland and some residential land. Akrotiri is surrounded by territory controlled by the Republic of Cyprus, but Dhekelia also borders on the [[United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus|United Nations (UN) buffer zone]] and the area controlled by the Turkish forces.\n\n[[Ayia Napa]] lies to the east of Dhekelia. The villages of [[Xylotympou]] and [[Ormideia]], also in the Republic of Cyprus, are enclaves surrounded by Dhekelia. The [[Dhekelia Power Station]], divided by a British road into two parts, also belongs to the Republic of Cyprus. The northern part is an enclave, like the two villages, whereas the southern part is located by the sea, and therefore not an enclave, though it has no territorial waters of its own.\n\nTerritorial waters of {{convert|3|nmi|km|3}} are claimed, and the right [[United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea|according to the laws of the UN]] to extend the claim of up to {{convert|12|nmi|km|3}} is reserved.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201213/cmhansrd/cm130325/text/130325w0002.htm#130325w0002.htm_wqn0 |title=Cyprus |work=Hansard |publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom |accessdate=25 March 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:20061019 Episkopi Bay.jpg|thumb|left|240px|Episkopi Bay is on the west coast of Akrotiri.]]\n\n== Wildlife and ecology ==\n\nCyprus is an important [[Bird migration|migration flyway]] for birds between Africa and Europe and [[Bird migration perils|millions of birds are killed yearly]] as they migrate over the island. To protect resident and migratory birds, [[BirdLife Cyprus]] and the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|RSPB]] survey areas of illegal trapping. More than 150 species of birds, over half of conservation concern, have been trapped in nets, or on [[Birdlime|limesticks]], and it is estimated that organised crime gangs earn over 15 million Euros yearly. The dead birds are sold to provide the main ingredient for [[ambelopoulia]] in the Republic of Cyprus; an illegal delicacy served to restaurant diners. The 2015 survey estimated a maximum {{Convert|19|km|abbr=on}} of mist nets across both the Republic and the British Territories, and more than 5,300 limesticks removed, mainly in the Republic. It is estimated that over 2 million birds were killed in 2015 including over 800,000 on British Territories.<ref>{{cite web|title=RSPB Mass killing continues on British military base in Cyprus|url=http://www.birdguides.com/iris/pictures.asp?f=433834|website=BirdGuides|accessdate=16 March 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161120211328/http://www.birdguides.com/iris/pictures.asp?f=433834|archivedate=20 November 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hundreds of thousands of birds still being illegally killed on British military base in Cyprus but annual increase halted|url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/news/416276-hundreds-of-thousands-of-birds-still-being-illegally-killed-on-british-military-base-in-cyprus-but-annual-increase-halted-|website=RSPB|accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> Employing measures such as covert camera surveillance (including a drone), exclusion zones and impounding vehicles, trapping activity at Dhekelia fell by 77,5%. In 2016 an estimated 800,000 birds were killed at Dhekelia and in the following year trapping activity fell by 77,5% and bird deaths to an estimated 180,000.<ref>{{cite news |title=Good news from Cyprus |work=Nature's Home |publisher=RSPB |date=Summer 2018 |page=40}}</ref>\n\nThe beaches in the British Sovereign Base Areas (SBAs) are important nesting sites for the endangered green ''Chelonia mydas'' and loggerhead ''Caretta caretta'' turtles. The SBA Environment Department, assisted by a large volunteer effort, has monitored turtle nesting success on SBA beaches since 1990. Disturbance to nesting turtles is an issue in some areas due to activities such as camping, driving on beaches and illegal fishing. Sea turtles in Cyprus are protected as priority species under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance (implementing the provisions of the Habitats Directive), enacted in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanctuary 40th anniversary edition: Around the regions - Cyprus Sovereign Base|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/469631/15-07-275_Sanctuary_Magazine__FINAL_lowres_.pdf|author=Dr Phoebe Carter|work=Sanctuary - The Ministry of Defence Sustainability Magazine, no.44, page 98|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, five [[Special Areas of Conservation]] (SACs) were designated in the Cyprus Sovereign Base Areas. The five SACs designated are Akrotiri, Episkopi, Cape Pyla, Dhekelia and Agios Nikolaos.<ref>{{cite web|title=Five SACs designated in the British SBAs in Cyprus|url=http://birdlifecyprus.org/en/news-987-Five_SACs_designated_in_the_British_SBAs_in_Cyprus.html|website=BirdLife Cyprus|accessdate=28 June 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160802100411/http://birdlifecyprus.org/en/news-987-Five_SACs_designated_in_the_British_SBAs_in_Cyprus.html|archivedate=2 August 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The designations were made under the Protection and Management of Nature and Wildlife Ordinance and will support the existing network ([[Natura 2000|NATURA 2000]]) of SACs in Cyprus and across Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frequently Asked Questions on the designation of Special Areas of Conservation within the Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia|url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/images/AEEIC/sac/20151217-ECO_SACs_FAQs_AECO.pdf|website=SBA Administration|accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{see also|Languages of Cyprus}}\n\nWhen the areas were being established, the boundaries were deliberately drawn to avoid centres of population. Approximately 15,700 people live in the areas. About 7,700 native Cypriots work in the areas themselves, or on farmland within the boundaries of the areas. The British military and their families make up the rest of the population.<ref>[http://www.indexmundi.com/akrotiri/population.html Akrotiri Population] and [http://www.indexmundi.com/dhekelia/population.html Dhekelia Population]. Retrieved 24 December 2013.</ref>\n\nPersons related to the territory may in theory be eligible to claim the [[British Overseas Territories citizen]]ship (BOTC status) through a personal connection to the areas (i.e., birth on the territory before 1983, or born after 1983 to a parent who were born on the territory before 1983); but unlike most other British Overseas Territories, there is no provision in the [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002|2002 amendment]] of the [[British Nationality Act 1981]] by which British citizenship (with the [[Right of abode (United Kingdom)|right of abode in the United Kingdom]]) can either be claimed through automatic entitlement or be applied for by means of registration, from or through a sole personal connection to the Base Areas. (In comparison, the 2002 act bestowed British citizenship on all other BOTCs.) Hence non-British and non-military personnel with the connection to the territory can only live and work in the UK through their EU (Cypriot) citizenship and not through their BOTC status.\n\nUnder the terms of the 1960 agreement with Cyprus establishing the Sovereign Base Areas, the United Kingdom is committed not to use the areas for civilian purposes. This was stated in 2002 as the primary reason for the exclusion of the areas from the scope of the [[British Overseas Territories Act 2002]].{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} {{As of |2010}}, around 3,000 troops of [[British Forces Cyprus]] are based at Akrotiri and Dhekelia.\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Akrotiri 01-2017 img11 Akrotiri village.jpg|thumb|Akrotiri village]]\n\nNo economic statistics are gathered for Akrotiri and Dhekelia. The main economic activities are the provision of services to the military, as well as limited agriculture. When the territory under the effective control of the Republic of Cyprus switched currencies from the [[Cypriot pound]] to the [[euro]] on 1 January 2008, Akrotiri and Dhekelia followed suit making the Sovereign Base Areas the only territory under British sovereignty to officially use the euro.<ref>Theodoulou, Michael. (27 December 2007). https://web.archive.org/web/20110510204604/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/europe/article3097521.ece Euro reaches field that is for ever England], ''The Times''. Retrieved 4 January 2008.</ref>\n\n== Media ==\n[[File:Akrotiri 01-2017 img01 BBC transmitter masts.jpg|thumb|[[BBC World Service]] transmitter masts in Akrotiri]]\n\n[[British Forces Broadcasting Service#BFBS Radio|BFBS Radio 1 and 2]] are broadcast on [[FM broadcasting|FM]] and can be widely received across Cyprus. [[British Forces Broadcasting Service#BFBS Television|BFBS Television]] is now only available to entitled viewers via satellite, having been confined to the SBAs or encrypted in 1997 for copyright reasons,<ref>[http://www.hri.org/news/cyprus/cmnews/1998/98-05-10.cmnews.html#02 BFBS pulls the plug on Larnaca viewers], ''[[Cyprus Mail]]'' 10 May 1998</ref> before BFBS switched off its analogue transmitters in 2009.<ref>[http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Screens+go+blank+as+BFBS+TV+switches+off+transmitters.-a0191740458 Screens go blank as BFBS TV switches off transmitters.], ''[[Cyprus Mail]]'', 8 January 2009</ref> The [[British East Mediterranean Relay Station]] is situated locally.\n\n== Transport and communications ==\n[[File:Britse telefooncel op Cyprus.jpg|thumb|left|upright=0.6|A British [[red telephone box]] in Dhekelia]]\nCypriot motorways pass through both areas. There is no public airport within the areas, but the [[RAF Akrotiri]] airbase is located there, which has a runway suitable for long distance flights, but not used for public flights.\n\nThe Base Areas form part of the Republic of Cyprus [[telephone numbering plan]], using the international prefix [[+357]]. Landline numbers are in the same eight-digit format, with the last four digits being the line number. Numbers in Dhekelia begin with the digits '''2474''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/british-forces-overseas-posting-dhekelia-cyprus|title=British forces overseas posting: Dhekelia, Cyprus|work=www.gov.uk|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> while those in Akrotiri begin with the digits '''2527'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/british-forces-overseas-posting-raf-akrotiri-cyprus|title=British Forces overseas posting: RAF Akrotiri, Cyprus|work=www.gov.uk|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> \n\nPostal services are provided by the [[British Forces Post Office]], with mail to Akrotiri being addressed to '''BFPO 57'''<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/482888/bfpo-indicator_list_7dec2015.pdf|title = BFPO Indicator List BFPO Static Postcodes|date = |accessdate = 3 January 2016|website = |publisher = UK Government|last = |first = }}</ref> and mail to Dhekelia and Ayios Nikolaos being addressed to '''BFPO 58'''.<ref>[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/278799/bfpo_indicator_list_11feb14.pdf BFPO INDICATOR LIST STATIC BRITISH FORCES POST OFFICES]</ref> [[Cyprus Postal Services]] provides postal service for civilian homes and businesses within the Base Areas, then using [[Postal codes in Cyprus|Cypriot postal codes]] and \"Cyprus\" as country on letters from abroad.\n\nThe bases are issued different [[amateur radio]] [[Amateur radio callsigns of the Middle East#Cyprus|call signs]] from the Republic of Cyprus. Amateur radio stations on the bases use the [[International Telecommunication Union]] prefix of \"ZC4\", which is assigned to Great Britain.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SjdQAAAAYAAJ&q=ZC4+radio+call+sign+cyprus&dq=ZC4+radio+call+sign+cyprus Amateur Radio, Volume 59, Issues 1-6] \"Steve Bowden, ZC4BX, recently returned to the UK after three years on Cyprus, where he initiated and managed the ZC4 award.\"</ref> There are about 52 amateurs licensed in this manner. Amateur [[Radio Direction Finding|radio direction finding]] identified RAF Akrotiri as the location of the powerful but now defunct [[Shortwave radio|shortwave]] [[numbers station]] \"[[Lincolnshire Poacher (numbers station)|Lincolnshire Poacher]]\". Several [[HRS antenna|curtain antennas]] there have been identified as being used for these transmissions.<ref name=\"Numbers\">{{cite web | title =  Lincolnshire Poacher | publisher = Numbers and Oddities | url = http://www.numbersoddities.nl | accessdate = 2008-05-25 }}{{Self-published source|date=June 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\n[[Service Children's Education]] oversees education for children of personnel and [[Ministry of Defence (United Kingdom)|MoD]] employees. The Eastern Sovereign Base Area is served by Dhekelia Primary School and Ayios Nikolaos Primary School, which are feeders for [[King Richard School, Cyprus|King Richard School]]. The Western Sovereign Base Area is served by Episkopi Primary School and Akrotiri Primary School, which are feeders for [[St. John's School, Cyprus|St. John's School]].\n\n== Travel documents ==\n{{main|Borders of Akrotiri and Dhekelia}}\n\nThere is normally no passport check at the border from Akrotiri or Dhekelia to Cyprus.<ref>[https://www.quora.com/Is-it-possible-to-visit-Akrotiri-or-Dhekelia-the-British-Sovereign-Base-Areas-in-Cyprus-as-a-tourist Is it possible to visit Akrotiri or Dhekelia, the British Sovereign Base Areas in Cyprus, as a tourist?]</ref>{{better source needed|date=November 2019}} Possession of a passport, or an [[National identity cards in the European Economic Area|EU-compliant national identity card]] is generally needed in Cyprus. A passport is required to travel between [[Cyprus]]/SBAs and [[Northern Cyprus]]. Issues concerning the validity of car insurance and customs are specified by SBAs' administration.<ref>[http://www.sbaadministration.org/docs/admin/announcements/Travelling_North.pdf SBA Customs and Immigration] Travelling to Northern Cyprus</ref>\n\n==Brexit implications==\nUnder Article 2(1) of the Protocol, the SBAs are partially part of the EU customs union in three domains: VAT, agriculture and fisheries. However, the SBAs are already outside the EU. Therefore, concerns have been raised about the future status of about 15,000 Cypriots (EU citizens) working in the SBA. Cyprus, [[Ireland]] and [[Spain]] are the only three EU states that conduct bilateral talks with the UK on the Brexit issue. The talks between the UK and the Republic of Cyprus started in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.eyes-on-europe.eu/brexits-impacts-cyprus/ |title=Brexit\u2019s obscure impacts: the borders of Cyprus |publisher=Eyes on Europe |accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dw.com/en/brexit-a-view-from-cyprus/a-40898512 |title=Brexit: A view from Cyprus |publisher= Deutsche Welle|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref>\nThe [[Brexit withdrawal agreement]] has a protocol on the SBAs, with provisions essentially keeping the state of them.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/PDF/?uri=CELEX:12019W/TXT(02)|title= INFORMATION FROM EUROPEAN UNION INSTITUTIONS, BODIES, OFFICES AND AGENCIES|website=eur-lex.europa.eu |format=PDF|access-date=2020-02-03}} page 136</ref><ref>[https://cyprus-mail.com/2020/01/31/foreign-education-ministries-reassure-cypriots-over-brexit/ Foreign, education ministries reassure Cypriots over Brexit - Cyprus Mail]</ref>\n\n== Criticism and disputes ==\nIn July 2001, protests were held at the bases by local Cypriots, unhappy with British plans to construct [[Radio masts and towers|radio masts]] at the bases as part of an upgrade of British military communication posts around the world. Locals claimed the masts would endanger local lives and cause cancer, as well as have a negative impact on wildlife in the area. The British and Cypriot governments jointly commissioned health research from the [[University of Bristol]] and the Ministry of Health of the Republic of Cyprus, and that research project reported in 2005 that there was no evidence of health problems being caused by electromagnetic fields from the antennas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electric-fields.bris.ac.uk/akrotirireport.pdf |title=Bristol University website |publisher=electric-fields.bris.ac.uk |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref> The Sovereign Base Areas Administration has carried out assessments and surveys into the effects on wildlife, which have fed into an \"Akrotiri Peninsula Environmental Management Plan\", published in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbaadministration.org/home/docs/eco/20121002_AKI_PEN_MGT_PLAN.pdf |title=SBAA website |publisher=sbaadministration.org |accessdate=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, the UK offered to cede {{convert|117|km2|sqmi}} of farmland as part of the rejected [[Annan Plan for Cyprus]]. \n\nOn 29 August 2013, during the [[Syrian civil war]], some Cypriot and British media sources speculated that long-range ballistic missiles, fired from Syria in retaliation for proposed British involvement in military intervention against the Syrian government of [[Bashar al-Assad]], could hit Cyprus, and could potentially deliver chemical weapons. In some Cypriot media it was stated that the proposed interdiction of the Syrian civil war, utilising Akrotiri and Dhekelia, could recklessly endanger the Cypriot populations near to those bases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2013/08/29/cyprus-placed-in-the-cross-hairs-of-syria-mess/|title=Cyprus placed in the cross hairs of Syria mess|work=cyprus-mail.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref> Two days earlier, on 27 August 2013, Cypriot foreign minister [[Ioannis Kasoulides]] had moved to calm Cypriot concerns, saying that the British bases were unlikely to play a major part in any intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cyprus-mail.com/2013/08/28/cyprus-will-not-play-major-role-in-any-syria-strikes/|title='Cyprus will not play major role in any Syria strikes'|work=cyprus-mail.com|accessdate=24 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Ayios Nikolaos Station]], in the ESBA, is an [[Signals intelligence#ELINT|ELINT]] (electronic intelligence) listening station of the [[UKUSA Agreement]] intelligence network.<ref>Jeffrey Richelson & Desmond Ball, The Ties the Bind: Intelligence Cooperation between the UKUSA Countries, Unwin Hyman, Boston/London and others, 1990, p.194 note 145.</ref> The UKUSA signals intelligence system is sometimes known as \"[[ECHELON]]\".<ref name=EP>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//NONSGML+REPORT+A5-2001-0264+0+DOC+PDF+V0//EN&language=EN |title=On the existence of a global system for the interception of private and commercial communications (ECHELON interception system), (2001/2098(INI)) |last=Schmid |first=Gerhard |date=11 July 2001 |format=pdf \u2013 194 pages |publisher=European Parliament: Temporary Committee on the ECHELON Interception System |accessdate=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Cyprus|United Kingdom|Geography|Europe}}\n* [[Index of Akrotiri and Dhekelia-related articles]]\n* [[List of British Army installations]]\n* [[List of British overseas territories]]\n* [[Murder of Louise Jensen]]\n* [[Sovereign Base Areas Customs]]\n* [[United Nations Buffer Zone in Cyprus]]\n* [[Overseas military bases of the United Kingdom]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*{{cite book|last=Fouskas |first=Vassilis K. |year=2003 |title=Zones of Conflict: U.S. Foreign Policy in the Balkans and the Greater Middle East |location= |publisher=Pluto Press |pages=93, 111 |isbn=0-7453-2030-9}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Akrotiri and Dhekelia}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* {{wikiatlas}}\n* [https://www.sbaadministration.org/index.php Sovereign Base Areas Administration web-pages]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/2794421.stm BBC News \u2013 \"UK offers to cede Cyprus land\"]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/1421365.stm BBC News \u2013 \"Cyprus protesters clash at UK base\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100101150457/http://cyprus-mail.com/features/remembering-our-baby-girl Cyprus Mail, Nathan Morley \u2013 \"Mystery of Dhekelia Cemetery\"]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100722235519/http://www.cyprus-mail.com/features/dhekelia-60-finest-barracks-world/20100718 Cyprus Mail, Nathan Morley \u2013 \"Dhekelia at 60\"]\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|ax|Akrotiri}}\n* {{CIA World Factbook link|dx|Dhekelia}}\n* [http://www.qaranc.co.uk/theprincessmaryshospital.php The Princess Mary's Hospital RAF Akrotiri]\n* [http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/commons/1960/jul/04/cyprus-agreement Cyprus Independence Agreement \u2013 Hansard Official UK Parliament Record]\n* James Rogers and Luis Sim\u00f3n. [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meetdocs/2004_2009/documents/dv/sede300309studype407004_/SEDE300309StudyPE407004_en.pdf The Status and Location of the Military Installations of the Member States of the European Union and Their Potential Role for the European Security and Defence Policy (ESDP).] Brussels: European Parliament, 2009. 25&nbsp;pp.\n\n{{Cyprus topics}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{British dependencies}}\n{{British overseas territories}}\n{{Countries of Europe}}\n{{History of Europe}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Akrotiri And Dhekelia}}\n[[Category:Akrotiri and Dhekelia| ]]\n[[Category:Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Cyprus and the Commonwealth of Nations]]\n[[Category:English-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British Army deployments]]\n[[Category:British military in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:British Overseas Territories|.Akrotiri and Dhekelia]]\n[[Category:Dependent territories in Europe]]\n[