)\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Athabasca|Athabasca]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Alberta, Saskatchewan\n| {{convert|7850|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|110|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n\n\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Nicaragua|Nicaragua]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Nicaragua}}\n| align=\"left\" | Rivas Department, Granada Department, R\u00edo San Juan Department\n| {{convert|8264|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|108|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|}\n\nIn 1960, the [[Aral Sea]] was the world's twelfth-largest known lake by volume, at {{convert|1100|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}. However, by 2007 it had shrunk to 10% of its original volume and was divided into three lakes, none of which are large enough to appear on this list.<ref name=\"sciam\">{{cite news | author=Philip Micklin; Nikolay V. Aladin | title=Reclaiming the Aral Sea | url=http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?id=reclaiming-the-aral-sea&sc=rss | work=Scientific American | date=March 2008 | accessdate=2008-05-17}}</ref>\n\n== By continent ==\n* '''[[Africa]]''': [[Lake Tanganyika]]\n* '''[[Antarctica]]''': [[Lake Vostok]]\n* '''[[Asia]]''': [[Caspian Sea]]\n* '''[[Australia]]''': [[Lake Eyre]]\n* '''[[Europe]]''': [[Lake Ladoga]]\n* '''[[North America]]''': [[Lake Superior]]\n* '''[[South America]]''': [[Lake Titicaca]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of lakes by depth]]\n* [[List of lakes by area]]\n* [[List of largest lakes of Europe]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n;References\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of lakes|*]]\n[[Category:Volume|Lakes]]\n", "text_old": "This article lists [[lake]]s with a water volume of more than 100&nbsp;km\u00b3, ranked by volume. The volume of a lake is a difficult quantity to measure. Generally, the volume must be inferred from [[bathymetry|bathymetric data]] by [[integral|integration]]. Lake volumes can also change dramatically over time and during the year, especially for salt lakes in arid climates. For these reasons, and because of changing research, information on lake volumes can vary considerably from source to source. The base data for this article are from ''The Water Encyclopedia'' (1990).<ref>{{Citation|last1=van der Leeden |last2=Troise |last3=Todd |title=The Water Encyclopedia| location=Chelsea, MI| publisher=Lewis Publishers| year=1990| page=198\u2013200| edition=2nd}}</ref> Where volume data from more recent surveys or other authoritative sources has been used, it is referenced in each entry.\n\n== The list ==\nThe volume of the lakes below varies little by season.  This list does not include [[Reservoir#List of reservoirs by volume|reservoirs]]; if it did, six reservoirs would appear on the list: [[Lake Kariba]] at 26th, [[Bratsk Reservoir]], [[Lake Volta]], [[Lake Nasser]], [[Manicouagan Reservoir]], and [[Guri Dam|Lake Guri]].\n\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n\n{| border=\"0\" width=\"10kjjj\n|-\n|colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=\"center\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n!colspan=\"7\" align=\"center\"| [[Continent]] color key\n|-\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\"|[[Africa]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\"|[[Asia]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCFF\"|[[Europe]]\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\"|[[North America]]\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFF66\"|[[Oceania]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FFEBAD\"|[[South America]]\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\"|[[Antarctica]]\n|}\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"800\"\n! align=\"left\" valign=\"bottom\" | Name\n! align=\"center\" valign=\"bottom\" | Country\n! align=\"center\" valign=\"bottom\" | Region\n! align=\"center\" valign=\"bottom\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Surface area\n! align=\"center\" valign=\"bottom\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Water volume\n!Salinity\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n| bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Caspian Sea]]<ref name=Caspian>The [[Caspian Sea]] is generally regarded by geographers, biologists and [[limnologist]]s as a huge inland [[salt lake]]. It is [[endorheic]] (having no outlet), and can be compared to other large (but still much smaller) endorheic salt lakes, such as the [[Aral Sea]], [[Great Salt Lake]] and [[Lake Van]]. However, the Caspian's large size means that for some purposes it is better modeled as a sea. Geologically, the Caspian, [[Black Sea|Black]], and [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] seas are remnants of the ancient [[Tethys Ocean]]. Politically, the distinction between a sea and a lake may affect how the Caspian is treated by international law.</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Azerbaijan}}\n\n{{flag|Iran}}\n\n{{flag|Kazakhstan}}\n\n{{flag|Russia}}\n\n{{flag|Turkmenistan}} \n|\n| {{convert|371000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|78200|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|1.2%\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Baikal|Baikal]]<ref>Lake Baikal is the deepest lake in the world and the largest [[Fresh water|freshwater]] lake by volume.</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Russia}}\n| align=\"left\" | Siberia\n| {{convert|31722|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|23600|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Tanganyika|Tanganyika]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Tanzania}}, {{flag|DR Congo}}, {{flag|Burundi}}, {{flag|Zambia}}\n| align=\"left\" | African Great Lakes\n| {{convert|32900|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|18900|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Superior|Superior]]\n| align=\"left\" |\n{{flag|Canada}},\n{{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | North American Great Lakes\n| {{convert|82100|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|11600|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Malawi|Malawi]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Malawi}}, {{flag|Mozambique}}, {{flag|Tanzania}}\n| align=\"left\" | African Great Lakes\n| {{convert|29600|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|7725|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Vostok|Vostok]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Antarctica}}\n| align=\"left\" | Under the East Antarctic Ice Sheet\n| {{convert|15690|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| 5,400\u00b11,600&nbsp;km\u00b3 (~1,300 cu mi)\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Michigan|Michigan]]{{#tag:ref|Although Lake Michigan and Lake Huron are usually considered distinct, they are sometimes regarded as a single lake known as [[Lake Michigan\u2013Huron]]. When treated as a single entity, it is the fourth largest freshwater lake by volume, at {{convert|8443|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://geology.com/records/largest-lake.shtml Which Lake is the World's Largest?]</ref><ref>\"Lakes Michigan and Huron are considered to be one lake hydraulically because of their connection through the deep Straits of Mackinac.\" Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory, part of the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]. \"[http://www.glerl.noaa.gov/res/Programs/glscf/hydrology.html Great Lakes Sensitivity to Climatic Forcing: Hydrological Models].\" NOAA, 2006.</ref><ref>\"Lakes Michigan and Huron are considered to be one lake, as they rise and fall together due to their union at the Straits of Mackinac.\" U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, \"Hydrological Components\" [http://www.edisonsault.com/CustServ/USACOE%20LS%20WATER%208%2007.pdf ''Record Low Water Levels Expected on Lake Superior'']. August 2007. p.6</ref><ref name=DEQ>{{cite web|url=http://www.michigan.gov/deq/0,4561,7-135-3313_3677-15926--,00.html |title=Great Lakes Map |publisher=[[Michigan Department of Environmental Quality]] |accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=geologydotcom>{{cite web|url=http://geology.com/records/largest-lake.shtml |title= Largest Lake in the World |publisher= geology.com |accessdate= 28 September 2012}}</ref>|name=longest|group=n}}\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | North American Great Lakes\n| {{convert|58000|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|4920|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Huron|Huron]]<ref group=n name=longest />\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}},\n{{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | North American Great Lakes\n| {{convert|59600|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|3540|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Victoria|Victoria]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Tanzania}}, {{flag|Uganda}}, {{flag|Kenya}}\n| align=\"left\" | African Great Lakes\n| {{convert|68800|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2700|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Great Bear Lake]]<ref name=EofEarth>{{Citation|last=Hebert|first=Paul| date=2007| contribution=Great Bear Lake, Northwest Territories| title=Encyclopedia of Earth |accessdate=2007-12-07| url=http://www.eoearth.org/article/Great_Bear_Lake,_Northwest_Territories| publisher=Environmental Information Coalition, National Council for Science and the Environment | location=Washington, DC}}</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Northwest Territories\n| {{convert|31153|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|2236|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Issyk-Kul]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Kyrgyzstan}}\n| align=\"left\" | Issyk-Kul Region\n| {{convert|6236|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1730|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|0.6%\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Ontario|Ontario]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}, {{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | North American Great Lakes\n| {{convert|18960|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1710|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Great Slave Lake]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eoearth.org/view/article/153100/|title=Search \u2013 The Encyclopedia of Earth|author=|date=|website=www.eoearth.org}}</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Northwest Territories\n| {{convert|27200|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|1580|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Ladoga|Ladoga]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Russia}}\n| align=\"left\" | Leningrad Oblast, Republic of Karelia\n| {{convert|17700|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|908|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFEBAD\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Titicaca|Titicaca]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Bolivia}}, {{flag|Peru}}\n| align=\"left\" | La Paz Department, Puno Region\n| {{convert|8372|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|893|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Van|Van]]<ref name=Degens_1984>{{Citation|last=Degens|first=E.T.| last2=Wong|first2=H.K.| last3=Kempe|first3=S.| last4=Kurtman|first4=F.| title=A geological study of Lake Van, eastern Turkey | journal=International Journal of Earth Sciences| publisher=Springer|date=June 1984| volume=73| issue=2| page=701\u2013734| doi=10.1007/BF01824978|bibcode=1984GeoRu..73..701D}}</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Turkey}}\n| align=\"left\" | Southeast Anatolia\n| {{convert|3755|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|607|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|2.3%\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Kivu|Kivu]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Rwanda}}, {{flag|DR Congo}}\n| align=\"left\" | African Great Lakes\n| {{convert|2700|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|569|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Erie|Erie]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}},\n{{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | North American Great Lakes\n| {{convert|25667|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|480|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Kh\u00f6vsg\u00f6l Nuur|Kh\u00f6vsg\u00f6l]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Mongolia}}\n| align=\"left\" | Kh\u00f6vsg\u00f6l Province\n| {{convert|2760|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|480|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Onega|Onega]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Russia}}\n| align=\"left\" | Leningrad Oblast, Republic of Karelia, Vologda Oblast\n| {{convert|9700|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|295|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Winnipeg|Winnipeg]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Manitoba\n| {{convert|24514|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|284|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Nipigon|Nipigon]]<ref name=Nipigon>{{cite web |title= Lake Nipigon |work= World Lake Database |publisher= International Lake Environment Committee Foundation (ILEC) |url= http://wldb.ilec.or.jp/Lake.asp?LakeID=SNAM-099&RoutePrm=0%3A%3B4%3Aload%3B |accessdate= 22 December 2014 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160304200835/http://wldb.ilec.or.jp/Lake.asp?LakeID=SNAM-099&RoutePrm=0%3A%3B4%3Aload%3B |archivedate= 4 March 2016 }}</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Ontario\n| {{convert|4848|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|248|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Toba|Toba]]<ref name=Toba>Although some parts of Indonesia are often regarded as belonging to [[Oceania]], Sumatra and [[Lake Toba]] are generally placed in [[Asia]].</ref>\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Indonesia}}\n| align=\"left\" | Sumatra\n| {{convert|1130|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|240|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFEBAD\" align=\"left\" | [[Argentino Lake]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Argentina}}\n| align=\"left\" | Santa Cruz Province\n| {{convert|1466|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|219.9|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Turkana|Turkana]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Kenya}}\n| align=\"left\" | African Great Lakes\n| {{convert|6405|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|204|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|0.24%\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[V\u00e4nern]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Sweden}}\n| align=\"left\" | V\u00e4sterg\u00f6tland, Dalsland, V\u00e4rmland\n| {{convert|5650|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|153|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Tahoe|Tahoe]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | California, Nevada\n| {{convert|496|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|151|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Dead Sea]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Jordan}}, {{flag|Israel}}, {{flag|West Bank}}\n| align=\"left\" | Judea and Samaria Area, Southern District, West Bank, Balqa Governorate, Madaba Governorate, Karak Governorate\n| {{convert|810|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|147|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|34%\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCCCFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Albert (Uganda)|Albert]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Uganda}}, {{flag|DR Congo}}\n| align=\"left\" | African Great Lakes\n| {{convert|5300|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|132|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Iliamna Lake|Iliamna]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|United States}}\n| align=\"left\" | Alaska\n| {{convert|2622|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|115|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Nettilling Lake|Nettilling]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Nunavut (Baffin Island)\n| {{convert|5066|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|114|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#FFFF99\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Balkhash|Balkhash]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Kazakhstan}}\n| align=\"left\" | Karaganda Region, Jambyl Region, Almaty Region\n| {{convert|16400|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|112|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|0.3% (variable)\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Athabasca|Athabasca]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Canada}}\n| align=\"left\" | Alberta, Saskatchewan\n| {{convert|7850|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|110|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n\n\n|- align=\"right\" valign=\"top\"\n|bgcolor=\"#CCFFFF\" align=\"left\" | [[Lake Nicaragua|Nicaragua]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flag|Nicaragua}}\n| align=\"left\" | Rivas Department, Granada Department, R\u00edo San Juan Department\n| {{convert|8264|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| {{convert|108|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}\n|Fresh\n|}\n\nIn 1960, the [[Aral Sea]] was the world's twelfth-largest known lake by volume, at {{convert|1100|km3|cumi|abbr=on}}. However, by 2007 it had shrunk to 10% of its original volume and was divided into three lakes, none of which are large enough to appear on this list.<ref name=\"sciam\">{{cite news | author=Philip Micklin; Nikolay V. Aladin | title=Reclaiming the Aral Sea | url=http://www.sciam.com/article.cfm?id=reclaiming-the-aral-sea&sc=rss | work=Scientific American | date=March 2008 | accessdate=2008-05-17}}</ref>\n\n== By continent ==\n* '''[[Africa]]''': [[Lake Tanganyika]]\n* '''[[Antarctica]]''': [[Lake Vostok]]\n* '''[[Asia]]''': [[Caspian Sea]]\n* '''[[Australia]]''': [[Lake Eyre]]\n* '''[[Europe]]''': [[Lake Ladoga]]\n* '''[[North America]]''': [[Lake Superior]]\n* '''[[South America]]''': [[Lake Titicaca]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of lakes by depth]]\n* [[List of lakes by area]]\n* [[List of largest lakes of Europe]]\n\n== Notes and references ==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n;References\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Lists of lakes|*]]\n[[Category:Volume|Lakes]]\n", "name_user": "94.128.85.232", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 939188581 byFlyer22 Frozen(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_lakes_by_volume"}
{"title_page": "Bita Moghaddam", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian-American neuroscientist}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate citations, [[WP:NAMEDREFS]] is needed.|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bita Moghaddam\n| image             = File:Bita Moghaddam 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Iran\n| nationality       = Iranian-American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Oregon Health Sciences University\n| alma_mater        = PhD at University of Kansas, Postdoctoral work at Yale University\n| known_for         = Discovery of first non-monoamine targeting compound for treatment of schizophrenia\n| awards            = Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU, Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research, Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology, 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award, MERIT Award from the National Institute of Mental Health\n| Institutions      = Oregon Health and Science University\n}}\n'''Bita Moghaddam''' is an Iranian-American neuroscientist as well as a Professor of Behavioral Neuroscience and the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience at [[Oregon Health & Science University|Oregon Health and Science University]]. Moghaddam investigates the neuronal processes underlying emotion and cognition as a first step to designing strategies to treat and prevent brain illnesses.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nMoghaddam grew up in [[Iran]] with her mother, father, and sister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Growing up in an environment where her parents emphasized the importance of education, Moghaddam came to learn that she could do anything as long as she put in the time and effort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\u00a0 In the late 1970\u2019s, Moghaddam moved to the [[United States]] to peruse her education. She graduated ''summa cum lade'' from [[Avila University]] in 1982 with a major in chemistry and minor in mathematics. She moved on to the [[University of Kansas]] to work on her PhD. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> When Moghaddam started her graduate education, she had intentions to pursue her dissertation work in chemistry, but was inspired by one of her professors, Dr. Ralph Adams, and his innovative applications of [[analytical chemistry]] to understand brain chemistry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After becoming fascinated by the neural processes underlying [[schizophrenia]], Moghaddam decided to pursue a PhD, and a career, in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/bita-moghaddam/|title=Bita Moghaddam \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Ralph Adams, Moghaddam could learn from a pioneer in the field how to build and apply electroanalytical tools to study schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electroanalytical.org/Adams.html|title=Recollections - Ralph N. Adams|website=electroanalytical.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Moghaddam worked on improving graphite electrodes for [[in vivo]] electrochemical experiments studying [[cationic]] primary neurotransmitters.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerhardt|first=Greg A.|last2=Oke|first2=Arvin F.|last3=Nagy|first3=Geza|last4=Moghaddam|first4=Bita|last5=Adams|first5=Ralph N.|date=1984-01-09|title=Nafion-coated electrodes with high selectivity for CNS electrochemistry|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899384909636|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=290|issue=2|pages=390\u2013395|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(84)90963-6|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1986, Moghaddam published a first author paper in the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] describing her improvements of the in vivo [[voltammetry]] method for applications in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=B.|last2=Adams|first2=R. N.|date=1986|title=Recent Developments of in Vivo Voltammetry: Applications to Studies of Chemical Dynamics in the Neuronal Microenvironmenta|url=https://nyaspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=481|issue=1|pages=106\u2013115|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|issn=1749-6632}}</ref> Moghaddam then published another first author paper highlighting her findings, using potassium-selective microelectrodes, that extracellular potassium concentrations vary across brain regions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Adams|first2=Ralph N.|date=1987-03-17|title=Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899387908031|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=406|issue=1|pages=337\u2013340|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(87)90803-1|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1987, Moghaddam completed her dissertation in which she simultaneously recorded the extracellular levels of both ions and neurotransmitters in the mammalian brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=7530811|title=SIMULTANEOUS MONITORING OF EXTRACELLULAR ION AND NEUROTRANSMITTER LEVELS IN MAMMALIAN BRAIN.|website=www.elibrary.ru|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After her PhD, Moghaddam pursued her postdoctoral training at [[Yale University]] in New Haven, Connecticut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Yale, Moghaddam worked under the mentorship of Dr. Benjamin Bunney in the Department of Psychiatry exploring the modulatory effects of dopaminergic signalling in the striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref>\u00a0Moghaddam published 6 first author papers during her 3 year postdoctoral studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=EX5b5sUAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Bita Moghaddam - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddem used the technique of in vivo [[microdialysis]] to look at the composition of extracellular [[dopamine]] in the rodent brain in various experimental preparations. She first discovered that the [[cocaine]] administration in rodents induced a higher magnitude increase in extracellular dopamine in the Nucleus Accumbens compared to the Medial Prefrontal Cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> In the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]], she then reported the effects of perfusing solution on extracellular [[dopamine]] levels and the downstream effects this has on dopaminergic brain systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1989|title=Ionic Composition of Microdialysis Perfusing Solution Alters the Pharmacological Responsiveness and Basal Outflow of Striatal Dopamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=53|issue=2|pages=652\u2013654|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Just before she began her faculty position at Yale, Moghaddam published another first author paper in the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]] reporting that administration of different antipsychotic drugs to rats has distinct effects on the release of dopamine in the Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens and the Striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1990|title=Acute Effects of Typical and Atypical Antipsychotic Drugs on the Release of Dopamine from Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens, and Striatum of the Rat: An In Vivo Microdialysis Study|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=54|issue=5|pages=1755\u20131760|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nIn 1990, Moghaddam started her first faculty position at [[Yale University]] in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She quickly rose to a full faculty position at Yale as she set up her lab to explore the neurobiology of midbrain dopamine neurons and prefrontal cortical subregions, key brain systems implicated in schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moghaddamlab.org/about-the-lab/|title=About the Lab \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In a study published in Psychiatry in 1991, the Moghaddam Lab reported that Ventral Tegmental Area dopamine neurons are activated both before stimulus onset, signifying an internal state of anticipation, in addition to firing in response to rewarding post-stimulus outcomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Totah|first=Nelson K. B.|last2=Kim|first2=Yunbok|last3=Moghaddam|first3=Bita|date=2013-07-01|title=Distinct prestimulus and poststimulus activation of VTA neurons correlates with stimulus detection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727034/|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=110|issue=1|pages=75\u201385|doi=10.1152/jn.00784.2012|issn=0022-3077|pmc=3727034|pmid=23554430}}</ref> Moghaddam continued to collaborate with her postdoctoral mentor and others at Yale to explore the effects of typical schizophrenia medications on brain chemistry in vivo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daly|first=Darron A.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1993-04-02|title=Actions of clozapine and haloperidol on the extracellular levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex and striatum of conscious rats|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304394093904832|journal=Neuroscience Letters|language=en|volume=152|issue=1|pages=61\u201364|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(93)90483-2|issn=0304-3940}}</ref>\n\nAs a young professor at Yale, Moghaddam started to hone in on the potential that aberrant glutamate signalling might be a large contributing factor to the pathology of Schizophrenia, so she began to explore glutamate regulation and modulatory effects of glutamate in the brain regions associated with schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 1994, Moghaddam found that stress-induced dopamine release is controlled by local activation of [[ionotropic glutamate receptor]]s ([[AMPA receptor|AMPA]] receptors and [[Kainate receptor|kainate]] receptors).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jedema|first=H. P.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=B.|date=August 1994|title=Glutamatergic control of dopamine release during stress in the rat prefrontal cortex|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7518503|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|volume=63|issue=2|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1046/j.1471-4159.1994.63020785.x|issn=0022-3042|pmid=7518503}}</ref> A few years later, she found that [[Metabotropic glutamate receptor 5|metabotropic glutamate receptors]] regulate dopamine release in the striatum, adding to the understanding of the diverse interactions between glutamate and dopaminergic system in the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Anita|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1998|title=Regulation of striatal dopamine release by metabotropic glutamate receptors|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291098-2396%28199803%2928%3A3%3C220%3A%3AAID-SYN5%3E3.0.CO%3B2-C|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=28|issue=3|pages=220\u2013226|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2396(199803)28:33.0.CO;2-C|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> She also made a novel finding regarding the regulation of glutamate release during times of stress, such that glucocorticoids, released as a result of HPA axis activation, inhibit the stress-induced output of glutamate in the prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bolinao|first2=Maria L.|last3=Stein-Behrens|first3=Becky|last4=Sapolsky|first4=Robert|date=1994-08-29|title=Glucocortcoids mediate the stress-induced extracellular accumulation of glutamate|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899394916225|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=655|issue=1|pages=251\u2013254|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(94)91622-5|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1999, Moghaddam and her colleagues tested the compound LY354740, a metabotropic glutamate receptor agonist, which they found to suppress aberrant glutamate release, reduced behavioral disruptions in animals given PCP, and overall have less side effects than typical benzodiazepines used to treat certain symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> These findings suggested that LY354740 could potentially be used to treat psychiatric and neurological disorders characterized by aberrant glutamate transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1999-11564-001|title=APA PsycNet|website=psycnet.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Moghaddam was recruited to the University of Pittsburgh, and was the first faculty member to be recruited straight to full professorship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam took on more teaching roles than she had previously at Yale, and she became a critical mentor to many young undergraduate students hoping to pursue opportunities in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam made many contributions to the field of neuroscience by continuing to probe how modulation of glutamate signalling affects behavior and neural circuit function in models for anxiety and schizophrenia. She then expanded her laboratory focus to understanding [[glutamatergic]] interactions and dopaminergic systems in adolescence since many of the symptoms of psychiatric conditions emerge during adolescence and targeting aberrant functions during this developmental period will be essential to preventing onset of disease in adulthood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moghaddam joined the faculty at the Oregon Health Sciences University where she is the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience as well as the Ruth Matarazzo Professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddam continues to probe the brain mechanisms involved in cognition and emotion in brain areas implicated in schizophrenia, anxiety, ADHD, and addiction, while also performing leaderships roles to oversee long-term planning and enhance collaboration within the OHSU behavioral neuroscience department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In addition to her laboratory and departmental efforts, Moghaddam brings extensive teaching experience from her time at Pitt and participates in a large array of outreach efforts and initiatives to promote women in science and young students to pursue careers in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwnoggin.org/2018/05/26/diet-vs-brain/|title=Diet vs. Brain \u2013 NW NOGGIN: Neuroscience outreach group (growing in networks)|last=Griesar|first=Bill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acnp.org/annual-meeting/honorific-grants/daniel-h-efron-research-previous-award-winners/|title=Daniel H. Efron Research Previous Award Winners|website=ACNP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* MERIT award from the National Institute of Mental Health<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Select Publications ==\n\n* Del Arco, A., Park, J., Wood, J., Kim, Y., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Adaptive encoding of outcome prediction by prefrontal cortex ensembles supports behavioral flexibility. Journal of Neuroscience, 0450-17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Bueno-Junior, L.S., Simon, N.W., Wegener, M.A., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Repeated Nicotine Strengthens Gamma Oscillations in the Prefrontal Cortex and Improves Visual Attention\u00a0 Neuropsychopharmacology 42 (8), 1590-1598.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Impact of anxiety on prefrontal cortex encoding of cognitive flexibility. Neuroscience 345, 193-202.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Wood, J., Bondi, C., Del Arco, A., and Moghaddam, B. (2016) Anxiety evokes hypofrontality and disrupts rule-relevant encoding by dorsomedial prefrontal cortex neurons. Journal of Neuroscience, 36(11): 3322-3335.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Lohani, S., Poplawsky, A.J., Kim, S.G., and Moghaddam, B. (2017) Unexpected global impact of VTA dopamine neuron activati on as measured by opto-fMRI. Molecular Psychiatry, doi:10.1038/mp.2016.102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Kim, Y., Simon, N.W., Wood, J., and Moghaddam, B. (2015). Reward anticipation is encoded differently by adolescent VTA neurons. Biological Psychiatry, 79(11):878-86.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. and Gur, R.E. (2015). Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting. Neuropsychopharmacology, 41(4):929-31.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Sturman, D.A., Moghaddam, B. (2012) The striatum processes reward differently in adolescents versus adults. Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, 109(5): 1719-24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Darrah, J., Stefani, M.R., Moghaddam, B. (2008) Interaction of n-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDA) and group 5 metabotropic glutamate (mGlu5) receptors on behavioral flexibility using a novel operant set-shift paradigm. Behavioral Pharmacology, 19:225-234.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2004) Targetting metabotropic glutamate receptors for treatment of cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Psychopharmacology, 174:39-44.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2002) Stress activation of glutamate neurotransmission in the prefrontal cortex: Implications for dopamine-associated psychiatric disorders. Biological Psychiatry, 51:775-787.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (1993) Stress preferentially activates extraneuronal levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex: A comparison to hippocampus and basal ganglia. Journal of Neurochemistry, 60:1650-1657.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Roth, R.H., Bunney, B.S. (1990) Characterization of dopamine release in the rat prefrontal cortex as assessed by in vivo microdialysis: Comparison to the striatum. Neuroscience, 36:669-676.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Adams, R.N. (1987) Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain. Brain Research, 406:337-340.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B., Schenk, J.O., Stewart, W.B., Hansen, A.J. (1987) Temporal relationship between neurotransmitter release and ion flux during spreading depression and anoxia. Canadian Journal of Physiology and Pharmacology, 65:1105-1110.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Media Coverage ==\n\n* Huffington Post, 22 March 2016, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_us_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba \u201cAnxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision.\u201d] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/anxiety-bad-decisions_n_56eb2012e4b09bf44a9cd3ba|title=Anxiety Could Be The Reason You Made A Bad Decision|last=Gregoire|first=Carolyn|date=2016-03-22|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Psychology Today, 17 March 2016, \u201c[https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process]?\u201d <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-athletes-way/201603/how-does-anxiety-short-circuit-the-decision-making-process|title=How Does Anxiety Short Circuit the Decision-Making Process?|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Forbes, 29 October 2012, \u201c[http://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/ New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults].\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/daviddisalvo/2012/10/29/new-study-shows-that-omega-3-supplements-can-boost-memory-in-young-adults/|title=New Study Shows that Omega-3 Supplements Can Boost Memory in Young Adults|last=DiSalvo|first=David|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* March 2016, \u201c[http://www.nature.com/multimedia/podcast/npp/npp_03212016.mp3 Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting].\u201d \n* SfN's first-ever podcast on \"[http://neuronline.sfn.org/podcast The Perils of Publishing]\"\n\n== Personal life ==\nMoghaddam\u2019s father is from the city of [[Tuyserkan|Touyserkan]] and her mother from Tehran.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Her father received a law degree from the [[University of Tehran]] in 1959 and served in the district attorney\u2019s office and then a judge for several decades. He is the author of several books in his native Persian including \u201cTouyserkan\u201d \u00a0\u062a\u0648\u064a\u0633\u0631\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u00a0on the history and culture of his birthplace. Moghaddam has been married to neuroscientist Charles W Bradberry since 1989. They have two children, Mazdak and Anahita. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moghaddam, Bita}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iranian-American neuroscientist}}\n{{cleanup|reason=duplicate citations, [[WP:NAMEDREFS]] is needed.|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Bita Moghaddam\n| image             = File:Bita Moghaddam 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Iran\n| nationality       = Iranian-American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Oregon Health Sciences University\n| alma_mater        = PhD at University of Kansas, Postdoctoral work at Yale University\n| known_for         = Discovery of first non-monoamine targeting compound for treatment of schizophrenia\n| awards            = Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU, Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research, Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology, 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award, MERIT Award from the National Institute of Mental Health\n| Institutions      = Oregon Health Sciences University\n}}\n'''Bita Moghaddam''' is an Iranian-American neuroscientist as well as a Professor of Behavioral Neuroscience and the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience at [[Oregon Health & Science University|Oregon Health and Science University]]. Moghaddam investigates the neuronal processes underlying emotion and cognition as a first step to designing strategies to treat and prevent brain illnesses.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nMoghaddam grew up in [[Iran]] with her mother, father, and sister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Growing up in an environment where her parents emphasized the importance of education, Moghaddam came to learn that she could do anything as long as she put in the time and effort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\u00a0 In the late 1970\u2019s, Moghaddam moved to the [[United States]] to peruse her education. She graduated ''summa cum lade'' from [[Avila University]] in 1982 with a major in chemistry and minor in mathematics. She moved on to the [[University of Kansas]] to work on her PhD. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> When Moghaddam started her graduate education, she had intentions to pursue her dissertation work in chemistry, but was inspired by one of her professors, Dr. Ralph Adams, and his innovative applications of [[analytical chemistry]] to understand brain chemistry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After becoming fascinated by the neural processes underlying [[schizophrenia]], Moghaddam decided to pursue a PhD, and a career, in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/bita-moghaddam/|title=Bita Moghaddam \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Under the mentorship of Dr. Ralph Adams, Moghaddam could learn from a pioneer in the field how to build and apply electroanalytical tools to study schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://electroanalytical.org/Adams.html|title=Recollections - Ralph N. Adams|website=electroanalytical.org|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nDuring her PhD, Moghaddam worked on improving graphite electrodes for [[in vivo]] electrochemical experiments studying [[cationic]] primary neurotransmitters.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gerhardt|first=Greg A.|last2=Oke|first2=Arvin F.|last3=Nagy|first3=Geza|last4=Moghaddam|first4=Bita|last5=Adams|first5=Ralph N.|date=1984-01-09|title=Nafion-coated electrodes with high selectivity for CNS electrochemistry|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899384909636|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=290|issue=2|pages=390\u2013395|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(84)90963-6|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1986, Moghaddam published a first author paper in the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] describing her improvements of the in vivo [[voltammetry]] method for applications in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=B.|last2=Adams|first2=R. N.|date=1986|title=Recent Developments of in Vivo Voltammetry: Applications to Studies of Chemical Dynamics in the Neuronal Microenvironmenta|url=https://nyaspubs.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=481|issue=1|pages=106\u2013115|doi=10.1111/j.1749-6632.1986.tb27142.x|issn=1749-6632}}</ref> Moghaddam then published another first author paper highlighting her findings, using potassium-selective microelectrodes, that extracellular potassium concentrations vary across brain regions.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Adams|first2=Ralph N.|date=1987-03-17|title=Regional differences in resting extracellular potassium levels of rat brain|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899387908031|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=406|issue=1|pages=337\u2013340|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(87)90803-1|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1987, Moghaddam completed her dissertation in which she simultaneously recorded the extracellular levels of both ions and neurotransmitters in the mammalian brain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elibrary.ru/item.asp?id=7530811|title=SIMULTANEOUS MONITORING OF EXTRACELLULAR ION AND NEUROTRANSMITTER LEVELS IN MAMMALIAN BRAIN.|website=www.elibrary.ru|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> After her PhD, Moghaddam pursued her postdoctoral training at [[Yale University]] in New Haven, Connecticut.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Yale, Moghaddam worked under the mentorship of Dr. Benjamin Bunney in the Department of Psychiatry exploring the modulatory effects of dopaminergic signalling in the striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref>\u00a0Moghaddam published 6 first author papers during her 3 year postdoctoral studies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?hl=en&user=EX5b5sUAAAAJ&view_op=list_works&sortby=pubdate|title=Bita Moghaddam - Google Scholar Citations|website=scholar.google.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddem used the technique of in vivo [[microdialysis]] to look at the composition of extracellular [[dopamine]] in the rodent brain in various experimental preparations. She first discovered that the [[cocaine]] administration in rodents induced a higher magnitude increase in extracellular dopamine in the Nucleus Accumbens compared to the Medial Prefrontal Cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benhamin S.|date=1989|title=Differential effect of cocaine on extracellular dopamine levels in rat medial prefrontal cortex and nucleus accumbens: Comparison to amphetamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/syn.890040209|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=4|issue=2|pages=156\u2013161|doi=10.1002/syn.890040209|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> In the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]], she then reported the effects of perfusing solution on extracellular [[dopamine]] levels and the downstream effects this has on dopaminergic brain systems.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1989|title=Ionic Composition of Microdialysis Perfusing Solution Alters the Pharmacological Responsiveness and Basal Outflow of Striatal Dopamine|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=53|issue=2|pages=652\u2013654|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1989.tb07383.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref> Just before she began her faculty position at Yale, Moghaddam published another first author paper in the [[Journal of Neurochemistry]] reporting that administration of different antipsychotic drugs to rats has distinct effects on the release of dopamine in the Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens and the Striatum.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bunney|first2=Benjamin S.|date=1990|title=Acute Effects of Typical and Atypical Antipsychotic Drugs on the Release of Dopamine from Prefrontal Cortex, Nucleus Accumbens, and Striatum of the Rat: An In Vivo Microdialysis Study|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|language=en|volume=54|issue=5|pages=1755\u20131760|doi=10.1111/j.1471-4159.1990.tb01230.x|issn=1471-4159}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nIn 1990, Moghaddam started her first faculty position at [[Yale University]] in the Department of Psychiatry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbrfoundation.org/about/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita Moghaddam, Ph.D.|date=2017-04-24|website=Brain & Behavior Research Foundation|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> She quickly rose to a full faculty position at Yale as she set up her lab to explore the neurobiology of midbrain dopamine neurons and prefrontal cortical subregions, key brain systems implicated in schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.moghaddamlab.org/about-the-lab/|title=About the Lab \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In a study published in Psychiatry in 1991, the Moghaddam Lab reported that Ventral Tegmental Area dopamine neurons are activated both before stimulus onset, signifying an internal state of anticipation, in addition to firing in response to rewarding post-stimulus outcomes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Totah|first=Nelson K. B.|last2=Kim|first2=Yunbok|last3=Moghaddam|first3=Bita|date=2013-07-01|title=Distinct prestimulus and poststimulus activation of VTA neurons correlates with stimulus detection|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3727034/|journal=Journal of Neurophysiology|volume=110|issue=1|pages=75\u201385|doi=10.1152/jn.00784.2012|issn=0022-3077|pmc=3727034|pmid=23554430}}</ref> Moghaddam continued to collaborate with her postdoctoral mentor and others at Yale to explore the effects of typical schizophrenia medications on brain chemistry in vivo.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daly|first=Darron A.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1993-04-02|title=Actions of clozapine and haloperidol on the extracellular levels of excitatory amino acids in the prefrontal cortex and striatum of conscious rats|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304394093904832|journal=Neuroscience Letters|language=en|volume=152|issue=1|pages=61\u201364|doi=10.1016/0304-3940(93)90483-2|issn=0304-3940}}</ref>\n\nAs a young professor at Yale, Moghaddam started to hone in on the potential that aberrant glutamate signalling might be a large contributing factor to the pathology of Schizophrenia, so she began to explore glutamate regulation and modulatory effects of glutamate in the brain regions associated with schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In 1994, Moghaddam found that stress-induced dopamine release is controlled by local activation of [[ionotropic glutamate receptor]]s ([[AMPA receptor|AMPA]] receptors and [[Kainate receptor|kainate]] receptors).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Jedema|first=H. P.|last2=Moghaddam|first2=B.|date=August 1994|title=Glutamatergic control of dopamine release during stress in the rat prefrontal cortex|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7518503|journal=Journal of Neurochemistry|volume=63|issue=2|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1046/j.1471-4159.1994.63020785.x|issn=0022-3042|pmid=7518503}}</ref> A few years later, she found that [[Metabotropic glutamate receptor 5|metabotropic glutamate receptors]] regulate dopamine release in the striatum, adding to the understanding of the diverse interactions between glutamate and dopaminergic system in the brain.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Verma|first=Anita|last2=Moghaddam|first2=Bita|date=1998|title=Regulation of striatal dopamine release by metabotropic glutamate receptors|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291098-2396%28199803%2928%3A3%3C220%3A%3AAID-SYN5%3E3.0.CO%3B2-C|journal=Synapse|language=en|volume=28|issue=3|pages=220\u2013226|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1098-2396(199803)28:33.0.CO;2-C|issn=1098-2396}}</ref> She also made a novel finding regarding the regulation of glutamate release during times of stress, such that glucocorticoids, released as a result of HPA axis activation, inhibit the stress-induced output of glutamate in the prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moghaddam|first=Bita|last2=Bolinao|first2=Maria L.|last3=Stein-Behrens|first3=Becky|last4=Sapolsky|first4=Robert|date=1994-08-29|title=Glucocortcoids mediate the stress-induced extracellular accumulation of glutamate|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0006899394916225|journal=Brain Research|language=en|volume=655|issue=1|pages=251\u2013254|doi=10.1016/0006-8993(94)91622-5|issn=0006-8993}}</ref> In 1999, Moghaddam and her colleagues tested the compound LY354740, a metabotropic glutamate receptor agonist, which they found to suppress aberrant glutamate release, reduced behavioral disruptions in animals given PCP, and overall have less side effects than typical benzodiazepines used to treat certain symptoms of schizophrenia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> These findings suggested that LY354740 could potentially be used to treat psychiatric and neurological disorders characterized by aberrant glutamate transmission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1999-11564-001|title=APA PsycNet|website=psycnet.apa.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Moghaddam was recruited to the University of Pittsburgh, and was the first faculty member to be recruited straight to full professorship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam took on more teaching roles than she had previously at Yale, and she became a critical mentor to many young undergraduate students hoping to pursue opportunities in neuroscience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.utimes.pitt.edu/archives/?p=43058|title=University Times \u00bb Neuroscience department lures Yale prof|last=Webteam|first=University of Pittsburgh University Marketing Communications|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> At Pitt, Moghaddam made many contributions to the field of neuroscience by continuing to probe how modulation of glutamate signalling affects behavior and neural circuit function in models for anxiety and schizophrenia. She then expanded her laboratory focus to understanding [[glutamatergic]] interactions and dopaminergic systems in adolescence since many of the symptoms of psychiatric conditions emerge during adolescence and targeting aberrant functions during this developmental period will be essential to preventing onset of disease in adulthood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Moghaddam joined the faculty at the Oregon Health Sciences University where she is the Chair of the Department of Behavioral Neuroscience as well as the Ruth Matarazzo Professor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> Moghaddam continues to probe the brain mechanisms involved in cognition and emotion in brain areas implicated in schizophrenia, anxiety, ADHD, and addiction, while also performing leaderships roles to oversee long-term planning and enhance collaboration within the OHSU behavioral neuroscience department.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> In addition to her laboratory and departmental efforts, Moghaddam brings extensive teaching experience from her time at Pitt and participates in a large array of outreach efforts and initiatives to promote women in science and young students to pursue careers in science.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nwnoggin.org/2018/05/26/diet-vs-brain/|title=Diet vs. Brain \u2013 NW NOGGIN: Neuroscience outreach group (growing in networks)|last=Griesar|first=Bill|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* Ruth Matarazzo Professor at OHSU<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://psychology.osu.edu/events/bn-area-presents-bita-moghaddam-ph.d.|title=The BN Area Presents: Bita Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} Department of Psychology|website=psychology.osu.edu|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Paul Jansen Award for Excellence in Schizophrenia Research<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Efron Award for Excellence in Research Related to Neuropsychopharmacology<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acnp.org/annual-meeting/honorific-grants/daniel-h-efron-research-previous-award-winners/|title=Daniel H. Efron Research Previous Award Winners|website=ACNP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* 2014 CINP Neuroscience Basic Research Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* MERIT award from the National Institute of Mental Health<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicine.yale.edu/ysm/news-article/13107/|title=Moghaddam appointed department chair at Oregon Health & Science University School of Medicine|website=Yale School of Medicine|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Select Publications ==\n\n* Del Arco, A., Park, J., Wood, J., Kim, Y., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Adaptive encoding of outcome prediction by prefrontal cortex ensembles supports behavioral flexibility. Journal of Neuroscience, 0450-17.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Bueno-Junior, L.S., Simon, N.W., Wegener, M.A., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Repeated Nicotine Strengthens Gamma Oscillations in the Prefrontal Cortex and Improves Visual Attention\u00a0 Neuropsychopharmacology 42 (8), 1590-1598.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Moghaddam, B. (2017). Impact of anxiety on prefrontal cortex encoding of cognitive flexibility. Neuroscience 345, 193-202.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Park, J., Wood, J., Bondi, C., Del Arco, A., and Moghaddam, B. (2016) Anxiety evokes hypofrontality and disrupts rule-relevant encoding by dorsomedial prefrontal cortex neurons. Journal of Neuroscience, 36(11): 3322-3335.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Lohani, S., Poplawsky, A.J., Kim, S.G., and Moghaddam, B. (2017) Unexpected global impact of VTA dopamine neuron activati on as measured by opto-fMRI. Molecular Psychiatry, doi:10.1038/mp.2016.102.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ohsu.edu/people/bita-moghaddam-phd|title=Bita  Moghaddam Ph.D. {{!}} OHSU People {{!}} OHSU|website=www.ohsu.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Kim, Y., Simon, N.W., Wood, J., and Moghaddam, B. (2015). Reward anticipation is encoded differently by adolescent VTA neurons. Biological Psychiatry, 79(11):878-86.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. and Gur, R.E. (2015). Women at the Podium: ACNP Strives to Reach Speaker Gender Equality at the Annual Meeting. Neuropsychopharmacology, 41(4):929-31.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Sturman, D.A., Moghaddam, B. (2012) The striatum processes reward differently in adolescents versus adults. Proceedings of the National Academy of Science, 109(5): 1719-24.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Darrah, J., Stefani, M.R., Moghaddam, B. (2008) Interaction of n-methyl-d-aspartate (NMDA) and group 5 metabotropic glutamate (mGlu5) receptors on behavioral flexibility using a novel operant set-shift paradigm. Behavioral Pharmacology, 19:225-234.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|title=Papers \u2013 Moghaddam Laboratory|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n* Moghaddam, B. (2004) Targetting metabotropic glutamate receptors for treatment of cognitive symptoms of schizophrenia. Psychopharmacology, 174:39-44.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moghaddamlab.org/papers/|